<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriots Ready to Discuss Reduction of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides said Sunday that the Greek Cypriot side is ready to
discuss as a prior issue the reduction of armaments on the island.
</P>
<P>
Clerides made the remark in a speech at the 18th annual march
of the refugees from the Turkish controlled north of the island.
</P>
<P>
"We will do everything possible to find a solution within the
framework of the U.N. decisions and resolutions," which provide
for a bizonal, bicommunal federation on the island, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added the Turkish proposal for a confederation in Cyprus has
already been rejected by the international community.
</P>
<P>
"Our political will is not sufficient. What is necessary is a
more determined intervention on the part of the international
community toward the Turkish side," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-led "shuttle talks," proposed by Secretary General
Kofi Annan, will be conducted by U.N. resident representative in
Cyprus Dame Ann Hercus. The talks are aimed at reducing tension on
the island and breaking the deadlock in the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Clerides said, "we will continue the policy of
reinforcing our defense with any weapon we consider strengthens
our security." This is the aim of the joint defense pact between
Cyprus and Greece, signed in November 1993, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said "our aim will be to find a solution to the Cyprus
problem through peaceful means, which will be just, viable and
functional."
</P>
<P>
He assured refugees taking part in the march that "we want a
Cyprus where all human rights are restored, including the right
of refugees to return to their homes."
</P>
<P>
The refugees held their annual march to protest the refusal of
the Turkish authorities to allow their return.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of an abortive coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has maintained 35,000-strong troops in northern Cyprus,
which was declared unilaterally by Turkish Cypriots as a breakaway
state, recognized only by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
