<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 50 Apply for Hangman Job in Swaziland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Swaziland has been
flooded with more than 50 applications from regions as far away
as Europe and Asia after it advertized for a new hangman, the
South African Press Association (SAPA) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted Swazi Justice Minister Paul Khumalo as saying that
he had received applications from Canada, Britain, South Africa
and even Japan. Khumalo said he had "more than enough"
applications.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland advertized the vacancy after its previous hangman
deserted his post more than 13 years ago and no local citizens
could be convinced to replace him.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland's last hangman was reportedly a South African,
"disappeared without a trace," in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
According to Khumalo, there presently were eight prisoners on
death row at Matsapa Maximum Prison.
</P>
<P>
"We don't need any experience or degree but the applicant must
be a very brave and classically educated person," He said, but he
was unable to say when his department would start interviewing
the applicants.
</P>
<P>
A recent upsurge in the number of death sentences delivered by
courts had forced the Swazi government to "revive" the practice
of hanging criminals, a senior official of the Swazi Justice
Department said.
</P>
<P>
The last execution in the kingdom was in 1983 when a
businesswoman was hanged for the ritual murder of her domestic
servant's son. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
