<HEADLINE> Yeltsin: Building Strategic Partnership with Uzbekistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said Sunday that during his visit to Uzbekistan he will sign an
agreement on bilateral relations and a 10-year bilateral program
for deepening economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told the Itar-Tass news agency before his left for
Uzbekistan's capital Tashkent Sunday morning that cooperation
between the two countries has become wider and more dynamic,
following his talks with Uzbek President Islam Karimov in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
"We have mutually defined our relations as strategic
partnership and comprehensive cooperation. They are based on long
history of friendship, mutual respect and sincere mutual
understanding," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
However, Yeltsin admitted that activities in the humanitarian
field fell far short of goals.
</P>
<P>
There are financial and economic difficulties, Yeltsin said,
adding that other things hindering bilateral relations were
reluctance and lack of vitality.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Yeltsin will discuss with leaders of
Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan the situation in Afghanistan and along
the CIS southern borders, Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
They will also discuss concrete steps for neutralizing a threat
posed by Afghanistan to the security and stability in the region,
Yeltsin added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
