<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM to Visit Turkey on Turco-Syrian Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTALYA, TURKEY, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa is to come to Turkey Monday on a mission aimed
at easing the current tension between Turkey and Syria.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Sunday afternoon by Turkish Foreign
Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan at a press briefing in the port
city of Antalya, where the Balkan summit will be held from October
12 to 13.
</P>
<P>
Utkan said that Moussa will deliver a message from Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak to his Turkish counterpart Suleyman
Demirel.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem is to meet with Moussa in
Ankara on the latest developments of Turkish-Syrian tension, Utkan
said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman denied that Turkey has seen some positive
responses from the Syrian side so far over the alleged Syrian
support of Turkey's Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has issued an ultimatum to give Syria 45 days to stop
aiding the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) militants and
threatened to use force to destroy Kurdish bases inside Syria if
Damascus fails to do so.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a guerilla war since 1984 for an
independent homeland in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria denounced Turkey's growing military alliance with Israel
which its says imperils Arab security and undermines its
bargaining position in negotiating for the return of the Golan
Heights, captured by Israel in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Ankara's threat of using force prompted serious concerns in the
Arab world that a military conflict between Turkey and Syria will
make the Middle East region more unstable.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak visited Ankara and Damascus last week in an effort to
defuse tension between the two neighbors, but no substantial
results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Syria have long been at odds over the PKK issue, and
share of water resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
