<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Opposes Foreign Military Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTALYA (TURKEY), October 11 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Foreign
Minister Zivadin Jovanovic said here Sunday that Belgrade opposes
any form of military intervention by foreign powers.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from his meeting with his Turkish counterpart Ismail
Cem, Jovanovic told Xinhua that the Kosovo issue is a completely
internal affair of the Yugoslav Federation and should be solved
under the principles of the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
Jovanovic said the Balkan summit, which will open Monday
morning in southern Turkey's port city of Antalya, is of great
importance for peace and security in the region and Yugoslavia
hopes that the meeting will make a contribution to the settlement
of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds have died and thousands others been displaced since
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic launched a crackdown on
February 28 against the ethnic Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army,
which is fighting to wrest Kosovo province from Serbia, the main
republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
About 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million people are ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Fightings between the Yugoslav forces and ethnic Albanian armed
groups escalated over the past weeks and the U.S.-led Western
powers have vowed to launch an air strike against Yugoslav
military targets if Belgrade refuses to withdraw its forces from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
However, Jovanovic declined to directly comment on the possible
the military strike.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a NATO member and enjoying close ties with ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, has agreed to send troops to join a possible
NATO mission in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkey also stressed that all political and
diplomatic means should be exhausted before a military action is
taken.
</P>
<P>
Prime ministers from the Balkan nations, namely Greece,
Romania, Bulgaria, Yugoslavia, Albania, Macedonia and Turkey,
will attend the two-day summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
