<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Progress in Afghan-UN, OIC Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The first day of talks
between the Afghan Taliban militia and the envoys of the United
Nations and the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) on
easing the present Iran-Afghan tension ended here Sunday with no
progress made.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General's Special Envoy Lakhdar Brahimi, OIC
representative Ibrahim Baker and Taliban representative Wakeel
Ahmed Mutawakil held two sessions during the day, but failed to
make any progress, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
AT the first session, Mutawakil, senior advisor to Taliban
leader Mohammad Omar, delivered a special message to Brahimi from
Omar inviting him to visit Afghanistan for detailed talks.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's chief representative in Islamabad, Saeedur Rehman
Haqqani, told Xinhua that the two sides actually did not talk
about Iran-Afghan tension, but instead focused their discussions
on events that adversely affected their ties in the recent past.
</P>
<P>
He said they discussed matters relating to Taliban-U.N.
relations against the backdrop of "some unfortunate events" that
led to misunderstandings between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"We apprised the U.N. team of the steps Taliban have taken to
address the problems faced by the U.N. in working in Afghanistan.
We also informed them about the progress of investigations into
the killing of one U.N. staff in Kabul a couple of months ago," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi and Ibrahim Baker, assistant General Secretary of the
OIC, arrived here on Thursday on the second leg of their mission
to reduce tension between Iran and the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and the Taliban were unable to finalize the venue for
their meeting until Friday, as Brahimi wanted the Taliban leaders
to come to Islamabad while the Taliban invited the U.N. envoy to
visit Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
A special Pakistani plane brought Mutawakil to Islamabad
Saturday night. He met Pakistani officials soon after his arrival
and discussed with them matters relating to the U.N.-OIC mission.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan played a key role in persuading the Taliban leadership
to come to Islamabad to save the U.N.-OIC peace mission from
failure.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi and Baker opened talks Friday with Pakistani officials
and they discussed various options for peacefully resolving
disputes between Iran and the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi's current visit to the region is in the context of
implementing the "Points of Common Understanding" that was reached
during the "Six Plus Two" Foreign Ministers' meeting in New York
on September 21.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers from Afghanistan's immediate neighbors
plus the U.S. and Russia evolved "Points of Common Understanding"
which include the cessation of hostilities in Afghanistan and a
number of confidence-building measures to promote the restoration
of durable peace in that country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
