<HEADLINE> Lesotho Rebels Agree to Leave Royal Palace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho opposition party
supporters, holed up in King Letsie III' s palace in Maseru for
the past two months agreed Sunday to leave for their homes, South
African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Vincent Malebo, spokesman for the opposition party alliance,
was quoted as saying that the 100 or more supporters had agreed
to leave the palace and "prepare for the re-elections" due to be
held within 15 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The presence of the supporters at the palace grounds was part
of a determined protest action by opposition parties against the
May 23 election result, which allegedly was in favor of the
ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili and his cabinet have
been pressurizing the king to remove the supporters from his
palace.
</P>
<P>
Mosisili accused the monarch, who is bound to be apolitical by
the Lesotho constitution, of taking sides and giving refuge to
opposition supporters.
</P>
<P>
In speech intended for radio and television broadcasts on
Saturday evening, Letsie appealed to opposition supporters taking
shelter in his palace to disperse and go home peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Some political observers believed that the move to remove the
opposition party supporters from the palace could help thaw the
"icy relationship between the Lesotho king and his government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
