<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: U.N.-Angola Difference Affects Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- As difference arises between
the U.N. and Luanda regarding the opposition National Union for
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), observers here expressed
worries that the Angolan peace process could deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
In early September, agonized by UNITA's failure in disarming
all its forces and handing over its key "territories" to the
government, Luanda cut off all contacts with UNITA led by its
chairman Jonas Savimbi and recognized the splinter UNITA
Renovation Committee as the only legal dialogist.
</P>
<P>
The government said it will work together with the Renovation
Committee to complete the tasks stipulated in the 1994 Lusaka
peace accord and solicit international support in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The government position has won support from the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) and from central African
countries, but was not accepted by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
On October 9, United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan
noted in a report to the Security Council that "These negative
developments pose serious threats to moving forward the peace
process" in Angola.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Angolan government and the UNITA to abide
earnestly by the Lusaka Protocol and make great efforts to avoid
the breaking out of another civil war.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Annan believed that the situation will be
complicated by dispelling one signatory of the Lusaka Protocol.
</P>
<P>
Although he put the total blame for the current crisis on
UNITA and its leaders, the U.N. chief still hopes that the peace
process be pushed forward with U.N. mediations.
</P>
<P>
Later, Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos asserted in a
letter to Annan that Savimbi will never give up war for peace as
indicated in the historical past. According to him, the only
possible way to settling the conflicts in Angola is for the
government to cooperate with the constructive Renovation
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The president tried to persuaded Annan not to have any
illusion about giving Savimbi another opportunity, which he said
is against the clear and righteous stand of the Angolan
government.
</P>
<P>
The new U.N. envoy to Angola, Issa Diallo, has assumed his
office for over a month, however, with no achievement.
</P>
<P>
He could not call the government, UNITA and the troika
observer countries (Portugal, Russia and the United States) to
sit down together for a joint committee meeting of the peace
process; his proposal for a meeting with Savimbi was also
rejected by the government on the grounds that no safety could be
guaranteed for him.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Annan has suggested to the Security Council that
the U.N. observer mission be given six more weeks after its term
expires on October 15.
</P>
<P>
If UNITA still cannot fulfill its obligations by then, and
dialogs cannot be held between the feuding parties, the U.N. will
gradually evacuate its personnel starting this December and pull
out all of them by the end of next January, Annan warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
