<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Supports Turkey's Stand on Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTALYA, TURKEY, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Foreign
Minister Paskal Milo said here Sunday that Albania supports
Turkey's stand on the current tension in the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with his Turkish
counterpart Ismail Cem, Milo said that Turkey, as a NATO member,
made "a best decision" on the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the Turkish parliament's approval of
Turkey's participation in a possible NATO air strike on Yugoslav
troops and police for their violence against separatist ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and his Yugoslav
counterpart Momir Bulatovic concluded their talks and left without
talking to reporters. No details of the meeting were available.
</P>
<P>
Milo, who headed the Albanian delegation to attend the October
12-13 Balkan summit in this port city of Antalya, said that his
country was urged by Cem to do more in settling the Kosovo crisis
which has "constituted a direct threat to stability and security
of the Balkans."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government has decided to provide four F-16
fighters if NATO launches air raids on Yugoslav military targets
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli Majko was not able to come to
the summit as a result of the continuing political turmoil in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Fierce fighting between the Yugoslav forces and ethnic
Albanian armed groups has made more than 280,000 refugees and many
crossed the border into Albania, according to Milo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
