<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Secretary Ends Visit to UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen ended a short visit here Sunday afternoon after
having discussions with leaders of the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
During his stay, Cohen met and had talks with UAE President
Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan on bilateral cooperation and the
situation in the Gulf region and the whole Middle East, according
to the UAE News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived here Sunday morning from Qatari capital of Doha
on the third leg of his Gulf tour. He has visited Bahrain and
Qatar and will also go to Oman, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
This is his first Gulf tour since U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania was bombed on August 7 that killed more than 200 and
wounded some 5,000 others.
</P>
<P>
The twin bombings are suspected of being related to Osama bin
Laden, a Saudi billionaire, No. 1 terrorist wanted by the U.S. for
a series of terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation in security with the Gulf states for U.S. missions
in the region is considered one of his preorities of being here as
he said in Doha, Qatar that the U.S. has evidence to believe
that a number of terrorist actions have been planned and an
attempt will be made to carry them out.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Doha, Cohen said to reporters that "we need
to work very cooperatively with all of our allies and all our
friends" to combat more terrorism actions.
</P>
<P>
In Bahraini capital of Manama, Cohen also said it has become
imperative for U.S. allies in the Gulf to acquire a ballistic
missile defense system to counter long range weapons owned by
countries such as Iraq and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. regards Iraq and Iran, which tested a long-range
missile recently, as major threats to the Gulf region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
