<HEADLINE> 2 Civilians Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Two civilians were wounded in
south Lebanon on Sunday in clashes between Lebanon's resistance
movement and Israeli occupying forces, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The two civilians were slightly injured when guerrillas of the
Iran-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, fired mortars onto the
Israeli post at the village of Rihan in the eastern sector of the
Israeli occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The fresh casualties raised to 53 the number of the Lebanese
civilians wounded in the south since the start of this year. Some
19 civilians were killed in the same period.
</P>
<P>
On the same site, two Hezbollah guerrillas were killed late
Saturday night by Israeli forces, the radio quoted the party
Sunday's statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah is spearheading a guerrilla war in Lebanon trying to
oust 1,000 Israeli forces and its proxy South Lebanon Army out of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in parts of south
Lebanon in 1985 claiming to protect its north from cross-border
attacks by Lebanese guerrillas. 
</P>
