<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Chancellor Takes Global Financial Plan to EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 11 (Xinhua) -- British Chancellor of the
Exchequer Gordon Brown is taking proposals of international
financial reform to his European counterparts as pressure grows to
solve the international economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to BBC ahead of his European Union meeting with fellow
finance ministers in Luxembourg on Monday, Brown called for
international "openness and disclosure" to help avert a financial
crash.
</P>
<P>
He attacked traders who "gambled" ordinary investors' money in
high-risk hedge funds, which place large bets on the movement of
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Brown said the three-point strategy to reform international
financial institutions would provide a structure which prevents
crises, rather than dealing with them as they occur.
</P>
<P>
According to BBC, the plan, already discussed with the U.S.
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, includes the follow aspects:
</P>
<P>
-- Introducing new international rules, such as transparency in
hedge funds;
</P>
<P>
-- Funding and reforming the International Monetary Fund;
</P>
<P>
-- Appointing a global financial regulator, who would oversee
economies worldwide, and report to governments through the IMF and
the G7 group of leading economic powers.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment we have a rather ad-hoc and piecemeal way of
approaching problems," he said. "I want a more permanent facility
that prevents crises rather than dealing with them as they arise.
</P>
<P>
"We have got to wake up to the fact we are now into an
inter-dependent economy where the decisions that happen in one
country affect another," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged Europe, as well as the rest of the world, to share
responsibility to create the conditions in which economic growth
and stability could be achieved.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to ask the 15 EU countries to provide billions
of pounds worth of extra funding to strengthen the IMF, a BBC
report said.
</P>
<P>
"We have all got our part to play. Japan has got to sort out
its banking system," he said, adding that "America has got to
resist protectionism and has got to vote funds to the
International Monetary Fund."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Europe had to work at reducing unemployment
and creating conditions which would keep the economy buoyant, he
said.
</P>
<P>
But he rejected suggestions that Britain was headed towards
recession, despite the fact that national growth would be only 1
percent, instead of the anticipated 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
He called the situation "a moderation of growth rather than an
absence of growth," saying that his "cautious and prudent"
strategies had ensured the U.K. was in a strong position to
withstand the fluctuations of the global economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
