<HEADLINE> UAE Urges More Investment in Energy Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Oil Minister of the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) has urged more investments in the energy
sector, especially in gas, to meet the growing demand of the world.
</P>
<P>
Obeid Bin Saif Al Nasir made the call when addressing the
opening session of 4th Middle East Gas Summit here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Nasir said natural gas consumption across the world will jump
by 45 percent in 2010 and by 85 percent in 2020, compared with
1995, which necessitates more investment in the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
The five-day meeting, which will deal with energy developments
in Asia, the Caspian region and the Middle East, and set prices of
liquefied gas, came as economic turmoil originating from Asia is
rippling through the world.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also study the influence of the current
economic and financial circumstances on the system of gas supply,
and on gas-related projects in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Major oil producers around the world showed up at the meeting,
including the UAE, Qatar, Oman, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Iran, Iraq,
Japan, Indonesia, India, Republic of Korea, Pakistan, China,
Bangladesh, Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Nasir, also holding the current chairmanship of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), pointed out
that the economic ills will last for some time and will directly
affect the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices hit a nine-year low in March and intensive efforts
are badly needed to stablize and enhance the energy sector, Nasir
said.
</P>
<P>
He urged producers, consumers and all other sides concerned in
the energy industry to continue their discussion to come up with
ways that are based on mutual benefits in the long run.
</P>
<P>
He also called on OPEC and non-OPEC members to cooperate to
prop up the energy market to serve the interests of all parties.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted oil and gas productions in the Middle East
account for 30 percent and 7 percent of the world's totals
respectively, while its proven oil and gas reserves each made up
65 percent and 35 percent of the world's total deposits.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East, as a sustained major source of power supply,
should make more efforts to meet the growing demand, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
