<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners Encouraged to Develop Nigeria's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 11 (Xinhua) -- A senior government official has
said that the Nigerian Communications Commission (NCC) would
encourage foreign investments and capital inflow into the
country's telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
NCC Chief Executive Ogbonnaya Iromantu told a forum of the
News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) held Friday in Nigerian capital
Abuja that such investment was welcome in view of the large
amount of money required for the extension of telecommunications
infrastructure in the country, NAN reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Nigeria requires a minimum of three million
telephone lines for its immediate demand and a minimum of 200,000
cellular lines in order to meet the minimum international
standard of one telephone to 100 persons.
</P>
<P>
The country's telecommunications needs would require not less
than six billion U.S. Dollars which is more than what local
financiers could cope with, Iromantu said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a national communications policy has been
formulated and will be published in order to enable investors to
position themselves to place their investments.
</P>
<P>
At the forum, he said his commission had introduced 10
publications to guide the development of the country's
telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
The NCC executive stated that standards in cellular network,
wavelength services, rural communications, deregulation and
tariffs, tariffs, tariff structure and perception of the industry
are among the subjects of the publications.
</P>
<P>
The commission, which is charged with monitoring and
supervising the telecommunications industry, has also published a
document to provide assistance and support for the on-going
privatization of the sector.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the NCC had held talks with operators of
Global Mobile Personal Communication by Satellite (GMPCS) with a
view to exploiting possible ways of participating in the GMPCS
services.
</P>
<P>
The talks are part of the NCC's initiative to launch the
country into the emerging global information village, he said,
adding the GMPCS services would provide "the easiest and fastest
mode of communication".
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian official noted that Nigeria's withdrawal from the
regional African Satellite Communications Organization is being
revisited.
</P>
<P>
"I am aware there is a ministerial meeting that is revisiting
the issue" and the outcome of the meeting would enable the
country to develop an advanced documentation on the issue, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
