<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Eager to Join WTO: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Commerce Minister
Usama Faqih said Sunday that his country was eager to join the
World Trade Organization (WTO), the official Saudi Press Agency
(SPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In a speech inaugurating the meeting of the Saudi Industrial
and Commercial Chambers Council, Faqih said his country would hold
the fifth round of negotiations with the WTO on November 16 in
Geneva on matters related to its accession.
</P>
<P>
Faqih hoped the negotiations "would proceed more rapidly so
that membership requirements could be fulfilled as soon as
possible."
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Ministry in charge of negotiations with the WTO
has presented two comprehensive documents, explaining trade
policies and foreign trade systems as well as service sectors in
Saudi Arabia, he said.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations began in 1996 and the coming round is
dedicated to highlight the main aspects of the Saudi economy and
the trade systems currently adopted, he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the fourth round held last December was the
real beginning of negotiations at bilateral and multilateral
levels to specify principles and conditions to get into the world
markets.
</P>
<P>
Faqih said his country had presented, during the past
negotiations, the primary offers of commodities and services, and
specified the needed flexibility and transitional periods to
implement the WTO agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi negotiation team made sure these offers meet the
comprehensive interest of various Saudi sectors and the demands
and interests of Saudi trade partners, he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier media reports said that Saudi officials had in private
expected that the Gulf Arab country would become an effective
member of the WTO before the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that being a full member of the WTO could
enjoy a lot of special privileges, including better opportunities
for exporting products to member countries on a priority basis
without any discrimination or barriers.
</P>
<P>
Another special feature of the WTO is the presence of a body
for settling disputes among members, which would help protect
Saudi markets from strategies like market flooding, Saudi
officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
