<HEADLINE> One Killed, 5 Injured at Lesotho Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 11 (Xinhua) -- A group of unknown
youths, allegedly armed with fire arms and a bomb were beaten by
supporters of the Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) Sunday
afternoon when the ruling party was holding a public meeting.
</P>
<P>
Enraged LCD supporters cornered the youths, who had
infiltrated the rally at Lerepeng Sport Ground, six km east of
Maseru, the capital, after a shot was fired, wounding an LCD
supporter in a knee, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The LCD participants beat one youth to death and hurt four
others. The meeting ended in chaos, unidentified witnesses were
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The shooting left LCD supporters scurrying for cover, with
some rushing to protect Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili and his
deputy Kelibone Maope.
</P>
<P>
Mosisili and Maope were whisked away from the rally shortly
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho's Police Commissioner Bolutu Makocaba said later that
one youth who had been attacked was found trying to plant a bomb
on the grounds. The LCD leadership blamed the opposition parties
for sending the youths to assassinate Mosisili and Maope.
</P>
<P>
The rally, to brief supporters on Southern African Development
Community (SADC)-initiated talks aimed at resolving the political
crisis in the country, was the first to be held by the LCD since
the SADC's military intervention on September 22.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 LCD supporters turned out at the rally.
</P>
<P>
At another Sunday rally in Maseru's Freedom Square, opposition
parties vowed to intensify the fight to install a government of
national unity.
</P>
<P>
The rally organizers accused SADC countries, especially South
Africa, of conspiring with Mosisili's government to deny the
opposition the right to a government of national unity.
</P>
<P>
The third round of multi-party talks between the ruling LCD
and opositon parties is due to be held on Wednesday, which,
hopefully, will pave way for peaceful settlement of the political
impasse in the kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
