<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Highlights Iran, Iraq as Regional Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen Sunday warned that the spread of missile technology
threatens regional security and stability.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before leaving Al-Batin military airport
in Abu Dhabi, Cohen said "the Iranian Shihab-3 (Meteor) missile
that has recently been tested poses, for example, a threat to
countries in the region."
</P>
<P>
The efforts of Iraq and Iran to develop weapons of mass
destruction also pose threat to the security and stability of the
Gulf region, he added.
</P>
<P>
The United States made intensive and costly research to develop
defensive anti-missile systems, he said, urging the Gulf countries
to take part in the research to acquire up-to-date defense
technology.
</P>
<P>
Cohen ruled out the possibility of improving the U.S.-Iranian
relations as far as Iran continues developing weapons of mass
destruction and opposing the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He also ruled out the holding of secret talks between the
United States and Iran to improve bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed appreciation of the moderate policy of
the incumbent Iranian President Mohammad Khatami in dealing with
the country's domestic affairs.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dhabi is thee third leg of Cohen's Gulf tour, which has
taken him to Bahrain and Qatar, and will take him to Oman, Kuwait
and Saudi Arabia. These are all members of the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC), an Arab political and economic group in the region.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. regards Iraq and Iran as major threats to the Gulf
region.
</P>
<P>
In Bahraini capital of Manama, Cohen said it has become
imperative for U.S. allies in the Gulf to acquire a ballistic
missile defense system to counter long range weapons owned by
countries such as Iraq and Iran.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of the deep friendship between the U.S. and the
United Arab Emirates (UAE). He said the two countries would go on
with their efforts to ensure security and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
He described his Sunday meeting with UAE President Sheikh Zayed
Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan as "highly significant."
</P>
<P>
He denied that his mission in the region is aimed at striking
military deals. The mission is aimed at strengthening the friendly
bonds and consultation between the United States and the GCC
members.
</P>
<P>
On NATO's possible air strikes against Serbian targets in the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo, Cohen said a decision on this matter
necessitates a unanimous agreement by the 16 NATO member states.
</P>
<P>
However, he predicted that the decision would be made within
two days to allow NATO forces to launch air strikes while
providing an opportunity to diplomatic efforts.
</P>
<P>
Up to 420 fighters are getting ready for the attack, he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the current Turkish-Syrian tension and their potential
conflict, Cohen said the U.S. supports the mediation efforts made
by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and hopes the efforts would
succeed in reaching a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
Asked about that appointment of Ariel Sharon as Israel's
foreign minister and its impact on the peace process, Cohen said
"hardline characters are sometimes needed for reaching
agreements." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
