<HEADLINE> Sultan of Oman Meets Cohen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Sultan of Oman Qaboos Bin
Said on Sunday met with visiting U.S. Secretary of Defense William
Cohen on the latest developments in the region.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two sides discussed the U.N.-imposed
sanctions on Iraq and highlighted the necessity of dealing with
Iraq according to the relevant U.N. resolutions, the Omani News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The talks also touched on the Middle East peace process. The
Omani leader underlined the importance of implementing the
relevant signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived in Oman earlier in the day from Abu Dhabi on the
fourth leg of his Gulf tour. He has visited Bahrain, Qatar and the
United Arab Emirates and will travel on to Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The tour is aimed at probing the possibility of creating a
defensive missile network in the Gulf region to protect U.S.
troops there.
</P>
<P>
In Bahraini capital of Manama, Cohen said it has become
imperative for U.S. allies in the Gulf to acquire a ballistic
missile defense system to counter long range weapons owned by
countries such as Iraq and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Security cooperation with the Gulf states is considered one of
his priorities of visiting the six members of the Gulf Cooperation
Council.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving Abu Dhabi, Cohen warned against the efforts of
Iraq and Iran to develop weapons of mass destruction that could
pose threat to regional security and stability.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. regards Iraq and Iran, which tested a long-range
missile recently, as major threats to the Gulf region. 
</P>
