<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GA Committee Opens General Debate on Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The First Committee of
the 53rd General Assembly (GA) Monday began its general debate on
a wide range of disarmament initiatives, including nuclear
non-proliferation, curtailing the traffic in small arms and
eliminating chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
Also top on the agenda will be to define the U.N. role in the
disarmament process, U.N. sources said.
</P>
<P>
The First Committee, in charge of disarmament and international
security affairs, kicked off its debate at a time when the
attention of the world is focused on disarmament issues with
particular intensity due to the underground nuclear tests
successively conducted by India and Pakistan in May this year.
</P>
<P>
As U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said earlier, those tests
tipped "the balance on which the nuclear non-proliferation regime
rested" and dealt a serious setback to decades of international
efforts aimed at disarmament and non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
Annan delivered a speech at the Monday meeting, the first of
its kind since the opening of a new GA session on September 9,
which was presided over by the newly-elected committee chairman,
Andre Mernier of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief touched on the relations between disarmament and
development, saying that "disarmament and development are
intimately connected."
</P>
<P>
"Disarmament lies at the heart of this organization's efforts
to maintain and strengthen international peace and security,"
Annan added.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Mexico, Austria (on behalf of the European
Union), Fiji, South Africa, Bangladesh, Malaysia, Colombia and
Myanmar are scheduled to take the floor at the debate, U.N.
sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
