<HEADLINE> Italy's Caretaker Cabinet Approves NATO's Use of Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Italy's caretaker government
Monday approved NATO's use of air bases in Italy for possible air
strikes against Serb targets in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
But the government also announced that only parliament can vote
to commit Italy to providing men and aircraft, or even logistical
support, for any military intervention by NATO.
</P>
<P>
The decision came after the Senate ruled Sunday that, although
it is only supposed to take care of day-to-day business, the
caretaker government can still implement international accords on
NATO's use of military bases in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Bases in eastern Italy have played a major role in NATO actions
in the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile in Brussels, NATO's 16 members began talks expected
to end Monday evening by transferring authority for intervention
in Kosovo to supreme commander of allied forces in Europe,
U.S. General Wesley Clark.
</P>
<P>
The decision has to be unanimous; Germany, Portugal and Italy
are expected to grant the necessary OK the same day for the
so-called "activation order".
</P>
<P>
The International Herald Tribune Monday reported that an
agreement had been hatched on a legal basis for air strikes in
Kosovo and Serbia itself.
</P>
<P>
Until late last week, when the government lost a confidence
vote and Prime Minister Romano Prodi resigned, Italy was insisting
on a new mandate from the United Nations Security Council for any
air strikes.
</P>
<P>
The NATO permanent council in Brussels is now reviewing the
state of talks in Belgrade aimed at averting military action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
