<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Institute Plans Staff Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Institute of Computing
Technology, an affiliate of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS),
plans to reduce its staff by 86 percent and retain a team of 100
professionals, mainly younger researchers, to conduct advanced
studies.
</P>
<P>
"The restructured institute will maintain close ties with the
Legend Group, the largest collective computer company in China,"
according to CAS Vice President Yan Yixun.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Yan disclosed, the institute will assist Legend in
forming a technology innovation center, and the latter will either
provide positions for staffers subject to downsizing or otherwise
provide support for related individuals to establish new ventures.
</P>
<P>
The new institute, which is expected to enter operations in
January, next year, will administered by a board of directors
consisting of CAS officials, the Legend president and outside
experts, said Yan, adding that staffer will be employed on both
short- and long-term contracts.
</P>
<P>
The institute, which was first established in 1956 and is the
most authoritative computer technology research organization in
China, has contributed greatly to the development of the nation's
hydrogen bomb, ballistic missile system, nuclear energy and
satellite technology.
</P>
<P>
The CAS holds 65 percent of share of the Legend Group, which
has been evolved from the institute's high-tech development
company into a collective group company with total assets of 1.6
billion yuan (192 million US dollars). Legend's 1997 sales volume
hit 12.5 billion yuan (1.5 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
"CAS plans to invest a substantial portion of Legend's profits
in the new institute," said Yan. "Some 50 percent of the funds
will be earmarked for applied computer technology research, with
some 30 percent going for frontier scientific studies and other 20
percent for basic studies."
</P>
<P>
Yan said institute researchers will receive average funding of
200,000 yuan (24,000 US dollars) and noted that the downsized
restructured staff will greatly improve the efficiency of research
and development.
</P>
<P>
"The institute and Legend will enjoy a mutually beneficial
partnership," said Legend President Liu Chuanzhi. "A central
research institute is essential for embarking on frontier studies
and the institute needs high-tech company with marketing
expertise."
</P>
<P>
The restructuring program for the Institute of Computing
Technology represents a new CAS approach to reforming the
scientific system, said Yan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
