<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Suffers Tracheobronchitis, Not to be Hospitalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
is suffering Tracheobronchitis, but will not be hospitalized, the
Interfax news agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has tracheobronchitis, with a body temperature of 37.2
to 37.4 degree Celsius and cough, when he was on a one-day state
visit to Alma-Ata, Interfax said. And his visit had to be cut
short from two days because of the illness.
</P>
<P>
It was also reported that Yeltsin is treated with
anti-inflammatory medicines and antibiotics, but doctors haven't
told him to stay in bed. Instead, they recommended he reduce his
work load.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president's spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin, who is
accompanying Yeltsin on the Central Asia tour, told reporters that
hospitalizing Yeltsin was not under discussion, and that Yeltsin's
doctors have not resorted to anything extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
Yakushkin said Yeltsin caught a cold since the weekend, after a
hard week of dealing with urgent social and economic problems and
serious international issues.
</P>
<P>
However, Yakushkin refrained from elaborating on Yeltsin's
symptoms, saying that he was not a doctor.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's plane is scheduled to leave Alma-Ata at 19:00 Moscow
time (15:00 GMT), and return to Moscow at about 23:00 (19:00 GMT),
Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin suffered two heart attacks in 1996 in the wake of the
June 16 presidential election. He also had quintuple heart bypass
surgery in November that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
