<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parliament to Convene Special Session on Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The German parliament will convene
a special session Friday to give a vote on whether Germany would
participate in a possible NATO military intervention in the
troubled Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellory Minister Friedrich Bohl made the
announcement Monday after three-hour talks between Chancellor
Helmut Kohl and his newly-elected Social Democratic successor
Gerhard Schroeder as well as Joschka Fischer, the Greens leader
who is tipped as foreign minister in the coming Schroeder
government.
</P>
<P>
Bohl also announced after the consultations that Kohl's
government would authorize the incumbent foreign minister Klaus
Kinkel and defense minister Volker Ruehe to vote for a possible
NATO intervention in Kosovo, including the participation of German
military aircraft, at relevant NATO meetings.
</P>
<P>
The administration of Kohl, who was defeated by Schroeder and
his Social Democratic Party (SPD) in Germany's general election on
September 27, has offered 14 German Tornado combat jets for a
possible NATO intervention.
</P>
<P>
The offer had been put into question recently because a
necessary parliament approval is difficult to arrange during the
post-election transition of government.
</P>
<P>
A special session of the old parliament will now fill the
vacuum, but controversies could still arise given the different
views of German parties on the legality of a NATO intervention.
</P>
<P>
SPD officials noted recently that in order to prevent a
humanitarian disaster in Kosovo they would favor a NATO
intervention even without a formal approval from the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
However, the pacifist Greens, which is the most likely junior
partner in the coming German government, has so far insisted that
a U.N. resolution approving the use of force should be the
precondition for any German participation in a NATO military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
A NATO council meeting scheduled for late Monday in Brussels
will discuss plans for a possible air strike against Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
