<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Region Copyright Symposium Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- More than 60 experts from 15
countries in the Asia-Pacific Region and representatives of
several international organizations attended a Monday symposium to
discuss new copyright treaties in the region.
</P>
<P>
The participants focused their attention of topics dealing with
a series of problems related copyright infringements and network
transmission technology.
</P>
<P>
While China has accelerated its efforts to protect copyright
during the 1990s, related infringements remain rampant throughout
the country due to the fact that an increasing number of highly
educated individuals have engaged in illegal activities, according
to Shen Rengan, deputy director of the State Copy Right Bureau
(SCRB).
</P>
<P>
China is currently revising the nation's Law on Copyrights in
order to provide better protection, according to Shen.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was jointly sponsored by the World Intellectual
Property Organization (WIPO) and the SCRB. 
</P>
