<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Wins Their First Chess Olympiad Women's Team Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ELISTA, October 12 (Xinhua)-- China's women team lifts the
Chess Olympiad Cup here on Monday for the first time since they
made their debut in the Olympiad in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Led by world champion Xie Jun, the Chinese women players
captured the title with an unbeatable 29 total points after
ensuring 1.5 points from three tactical draws with Bulgaria in
the last round.
</P>
<P>
China was only a 0.5 point away from their ever first world
title before Monday's matches. China widened their lead to 2.5
point over the second-placed Georgia after whitewashing Hungary
3-0 in the 13th round.
</P>
<P>
The victory marked another milestone for the China women's
team after Xie Jun claimed the women's individual title in 1991
which has long been a patent for Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Olympiad featured 74 teams including the three chess
powers-- Georgia, Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
China took over the lead since the fifth round and their
momentum was culminated during the fourth to eighth rounds to
establish a collect 14 points from fifteen games.
</P>
<P>
After the 10th round China's lead ahead the closest rivals was
reduced to two points as they lost to Georgia, and further
dwindled to 1.5 as they were forced to a draw with Russia in the
following round.
</P>
<P>
the Chinese girls faced no serious challenged in the last two
rounds before they lifted the trophy with an unassailable
advantage.
</P>
<P>
China women's chess team has came in third in the 1990 Olmpiad
and second in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
