<HEADLINE> German Cabinet Gives Go-Ahead to NATO Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The German caretaker government
has given the green light to a possible NATO air attack on
Yugoslavia over the Kosovo crisis, Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
said Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a special cabinet meeting in Bonn, Kinkel said
that the German government was deeply worried about the situation
in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, where about 290,000 civilians
had fled their homes due to attacks launched by Serbian security
forces.
</P>
<P>
"Now it is serious for a NATO attack," Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
An approval by all governments of 16 NATO members is necessary
for a NATO ambassadors meeting later this afternoon in Brussels,
during which a decision would be made on whether to give the
"activation order" for a military intervention.
</P>
<P>
Once the order is given, attacks could be launched by NATO
forces without further consultation.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Kinkel confirmed that the German parliament
would convene a special session Friday to vote on Germany's
participation in the possible NATO intervention.
</P>
<P>
The government of Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who was defeated by
Gerhard Schroeder and his Social Democratic Party in Germany's
September 27 general election, has offered 14 German Tornado
combat jets for a possible NATO strike against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
