<HEADLINE> Erekat: Palestinians Ready for Washington Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian side is well
prepared for the upcoming Washington summit which will focus on
breaking the stalemate of the Mideast peace process, said a senior
Palestinian official on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Saeb Erekat, Palestinian chief negotiator, said the Palestinian
side has completed its preparations and reports on various issues
to be discussed during the Washington summit among U.S. President
Bill Clinton, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
All these reports have been approved by Arafat, Erekat told the
Voice of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
The Washington summit will discuss the scope of Israel's troop
redeployment in the West Bank and the Palestinian side has also
prepared maps for that, he said.
</P>
<P>
Erekat also expressed hope that the Israeli side would adopt a
positive attitude towards the Washington summit.
</P>
<P>
During U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's trip here
early this month, Arafat and Netanyahu agreed to attend the
Washington summit with Clinton due Thursday. The three-day
meetings will take place at three locations in the Washington DC
area.
</P>
<P>
In preparation for the summit, Arafat called a meeting of the
Palestinian leadership in the West Bank city of Ramallah Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Arafat flew to Amman and briefed Jordan's Crown
Prince Hassan on the Palestinian positions on various issues to be
taken up at the summit.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is scheduled to leave for Washington on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu is to call his inner cabinet ministers
for a meeting Monday evening to prepare Israel's position for the
summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
