<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Doping Chief Quits Amid Drug Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 12 (Xinhua)-- Italy's anti-doping chief Ugo
Longo tendered his resignation here to the Italian Olympic
Committee (CONI) for "work reasons" on Monday amid a haunting
doping scandal in Italy soccer.
</P>
<P>
Longo was the head of the anti-doping prosecution service
under CONI, the ruling body for national sport, whose own
president, Mario Pescante, quit exactly two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Longo's service had failed to show any tangible results in two
years' work, while Longo had concluded a doping inquiry in August
saying that the phenomenon simply did not exist in Italian soccer.
</P>
<P>
The past six weeks, however, have seen a string of damaging
revelations about claims of widespread drug test failures and
cover-ups.
</P>
<P>
Italy's dope test laboratory has been closed down and all its
officials were sacked.
</P>
<P>
Longo's service, one of three parts to the bureaucracy of
doping officialdom in Italy, is responsible for investigating
allegations of doping by an athlete and making a recommendation
to a separate commission of inquiry.
</P>
<P>
The commission considers them before making its own
recommendations to the athlete's sporting federation, such as
cycling or football, who then take any sanctions they consider
necessary.
</P>
<P>
But Longo's recommendations have been systematically ignored
by both the doping commission and the major sports federations,
rendering his team's efforts largely pointless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
