<HEADLINE> 466 Mayors Elected in Greece's Local Government Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Mayors were elected in 466 out
of a total of 898 municipalities in the first round of Greece's
local government elections on Sunday, Greece's Interior Ministry
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some 8.9 million registered voters participated in Sunday's
elections, the first after the merging of a multitude of small
communities into larger municipal units in Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greece's main opposition New Democracy-backed mayoral
candidates were elected in 119 municipalities and the ruling
Panhellenic Socialist Movement-backed mayoral candidates in 91
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
Mayors elected in the remaining municipalities were backed by
combination of parties in the country.
</P>
<P>
Of a total of 54 prefectures, 15 prefects were elected with the
ruling Panhellenic Socialist Movement-backed prefects being
elected in eight prefectures and New Democracy-backed prefects in
seven prefectures.
</P>
<P>
In the Greek capital of Athens, incumbent mayor Dimitris
Avramopoulos was re-elected by having won 57.68 percent of the
votes.
</P>
<P>
Run-offs will take place next Sunday in the three other major
cities of Piraeus, Thessaloniki and Patras.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the elections, Greek government spokesman Yannis
Nicolaou said Monday that the outcome of Sunday's polls did not
have any immediate impact on the government's work.
</P>
<P>
He denied reports of an imminent government reshuffle or that
the results of the polls would lead to any changes in the Greek
government's priorities and goals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
