<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Warn Yellow River Faces Peril </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists warn any
failure to adopt rational water conservancy measures will subject
the Yellow River to the possibility of major flood disasters,
interrupted water flow and course changes.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River Valley, home to China's second longest river
following the Yangtze, has long been regarded as the "Cradle of
Chinese Civilization."
</P>
<P>
A recent report by the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS)
indicates frequent interrupted water flow in the lower reaches of
the river, with some 90 percent of silt accumulating in the main
river channel. Silting which has raised the riverbed above the
surrounding natural ground level has created a critical in what
scientists refer to as the "elevated river".
</P>
<P>
CAS Academician Liu Changming noted that prevailing conditions
seriously threaten the river's normal water volume and will
eventually create extremely grave situation.
</P>
<P>
"Generally speaking, the Yellow River experiences a course
change once each century, with current conditions in the lower
reaches similar to those which led to the last course change in
1855," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
He warned that major flooding will adversely affect some 78
million people living in a 120,000 sq.km. area.
</P>
<P>
Liu and an expert team organized by the CAS and the Chinese
Academy of Engineering visited four provinces in the lower and
middle reaches of the Yellow River in July to document existing
problems.
</P>
<P>
Interrupted water flow in the lower reaches of the river
increased in both frequency and severity since the the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The CAS report indicated that Lijin Hydrometric Station in east
China's Shandong Province at the Bohai Sea estuary, reported dry
conditions for 330 days during 1997. Water ceased flowing in
sections of the river stretching a total of 704 kilometers, with
90 percent of the sections located in the lower reaches.
</P>
<P>
Major tributaries in the middle reaches of the Yellow River
have also been subject to frequent interrupted water flows, and
scientists noted the distinct possibility that the Yellow River
will become nothing more than a "seasonal river."
</P>
<P>
Prolonged droughts increase salinization in the river delta
soil and create an imbalanced ecosystem which threatens over 8,000
species of marine animals, more than 100 varieties of wild of
plants and 180 species birds, said Liu.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River Report outlining problems and offering
suggestions has been submitted to the State Council, China's
highest governing body.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ISF Chief: Friendship Comes First at World Gymnasiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The '98 International
Schoolsports Federational (ISF) World Gymnasiade, a sports meet
for the highschool students, will make further contribution to
the growth of high school sports in the world, ISF president Jean
Louis Boujon said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Boujon said at a news conference that the ISF World
Gymnasiade, born in Europe, cannot develop fully without the
participation of all member countries.
</P>
<P>
"For this reason, Shanghai's application to host the students
games this year was approved by ISF, making it the first one to
be held outside Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
The '98 World Gymnasiade will open here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Before we came to China, we were worried about the
communication with the Chinese side. However, I can see clearly
that the local people are trying hard for the success of the
Gymnasiade," Boujon said.
</P>
<P>
"All the athletes are happy to come to China and it's a good
chance for young people from around the world to gather and
communicate with each other. At the same time, the event will
make the city better known," Boujon said.
</P>
<P>
The president added that sports is an important and useful
part of education.
</P>
<P>
"The ISF hope sports will be an efficient channel through
which young people of the world can learn from each other and
promote their friendly affection. The purpose of the ISF is to
educate by sports and enhance friendship through sports," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"In this way, the spirit of the Gymnasiade is more than
competition. All the young athletes pay more attention to the
friendship among them, established through sports.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a fair competition without doping and violence."
</P>
<P>
Boujon also explained the reason that the gymnasiade features
only four events -- track and field, swimming, gymnastics and
rhythmic gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
"The game is designed to fit in with the sport education for
high school students. These four sports are also popular in the
world, making it possible to gather student athletes from various
parts of the world, " he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
