<HEADLINE> Reconstructed Ancient Chinese Instruments Play New Songs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Preciously reconstructed
Chinese musical instruments exported to Japan in ancient times
will be played in the "Echoes of The Silk Road," which include
world premiere of works by renowned composers.
</P>
<P>
The "Echoes of The Silk Road" is a music program of the
forthcoming Festival of Asian Arts (FAA) slated for October 23 to
November 14 this year in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
With a mission of reconstructing and restoring ancient musical
instruments, the "Echoes of The Silk Road" project not only marks
the success of joint research between Chinese and Japanese music
scholars, but also inspires the music creation in Asia for the
next century.
</P>
<P>
Dated back to the prosperous Tang Dynasty over 1,000 years ago,
China exported large quantity of musical instruments to Japan
lying in the east of the Silk Road. These instruments, highly
valued by Japan, have been well kept at Shosoin in Nara and
survive till now.
</P>
<P>
Since 1975, Japan has started the research on these ancient
musical instruments imported from China, aiming at restoring them
for performance and exhibition.
</P>
<P>
In the FAA, the "Echoes of The Silk Road" will feature two
captivating concerts, one exhibition and one seminar, interacting
to full extent to reveal the charm of news songs by the
reconstructed instruments.
</P>
<P>
The restored instruments are now being displayed at the Hong
Kong Cultural Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
