<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Envoy to Visit Afghanistan Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.N. Secretary
General's Special Envoy on Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi decided
here Monday to visit the Afghan Taliban's headquarters in Kandahar
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Brahimi has accepted Taliban leader Mohammad Omar's invitation
and assured us that he will proceed to Kandahar on October 14 for
talks," the chief representative of the Taliban in Islamabad,
Saeedur Rahman Haqqani, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Along with Ibrahim Baker, assistant secretary general of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference, Brahimi held the third
round of talks with Wakeel Ahmad Mutawakil, a senior advisor to
Omar, Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
During the two-hour long talks, the two sides further dilated
on their respective positions on all aspects of their discussion,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The two sides held two sessions of talks here Sunday but
achieved no results.
</P>
<P>
Omar had invited Brahimi for talks to the Taliban militia
stronghold of Kandahar while Brahimi had insisted that the Taliban
send representatives to Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Mutawakil flew into Islamabad on Saturday night carrying a
letter for Brahimi from Omar who in his letter reiterated his
invitation to the U.N. envoy to hold talks in Afghanistan instead
of in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy is on a visit to the region following the Six
Plus Two meeting among Afghanistan's six immediate neighbors and
the United States and Russia in New York on September 21. The
meeting had called for despatching the U.N. secretary general's
envoy on Afghanistan to bring a peaceful end to the standoff
between Iran and the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Before flying here Thursday night, Brahimi spent four days in
Teheran as part of his peace mission last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
