<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Affairs Minister Wins United Nations Award (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Minister of Civil Affairs Doje
Cering recently received an international disaster prevention
award from the United Nations, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also reported that Professor Wang Angsheng,
director of the Natural Disaster Reduction Center under the
Chinese Academy of Sciences, won the Sasakawa Disaster Prevention
Award named after a prominent Japanese philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
Doje was the first Chinese government official and Wang the
nation's first scientist to receive the honors which are presented
annually to individuals engaged in humanitarian activities or
scientific research centered on reducing casualties and property
losses resulting from natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
"The awards represents the international community's
acknowledgement of China's painstaking efforts to reduce the
impact of all types of disasters, and our monumental victory over
this summer's record flooding," according to an official of the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
Heavy flooding hit the entire Yangtze River Valley and
northeast China's Nenjiang and Songhua river basins between July
and September. The Chinese government mobilized millions of
civilians and over 300,000 soldiers to join the flood control
effort.
</P>
<P>
The UN Natural Disaster Reduction Decade Committee (NDRDC)
reportedly selected Doje and Wang from more than 50 candidates
from around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Affairs Minister Wins United Nations Award (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two winners are expected to fly to the NDRDC headquarters
in Geneva to receive the awards on October 14 and introduce China's
disaster reduction and prevention efforts.
</P>
<P>
The 42nd UN General Assembly passed a 1997 resolution naming
the last ten years of this century as the "International Decade for
Natural Disaster Reduction". The NDRDC was established the same
year.
</P>
<P>
China formed the "China Committee of the International Decade
for Natural Disaster Reduction" in April, 1989, with members
coming from 28 central government departments and research
institutes involved in disaster relief and prevention.
</P>
<P>
Doje currently serve the vice director of the committee, with
Wang head of the related panel of experts.
</P>
<P>
The committee not only plays an active role in the country's
major disaster relief programs, but also compiled the first Work
Report on Natural Disaster Reduction in China and formulated
China's Natural Disaster Reduction Program for 1998-2010.
</P>
<P>
The committee is currently engaged in active efforts to
promote the establishment of a Natural Disaster Reduction Center
which will mobilize various resources to respond to natural
disasters nationwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Student Product Trade Fair Closes in Nanning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Second International
Student Product Trade Fair closed today in Nanning, capital of
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, with a total
business volume of 629 million yuan (75.8 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
More than 1,500 companies from both at home and overseas
attended the four-day fair and exhibited over 40,000 products such
as computers, games, clothing, shoes and textbooks.
</P>
<P>
Nanning hosted the first highly-successful fair last October,
said Mayer Lin Guoqiang, adding that plans call for expanding the
overall scale of the event.  
</P>
