<HEADLINE> Cold, Kosovo Crisis Prompt Yeltsin to Shorten State Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
decided to cut short his Kazakhstan visit because of his cold and
Moscow's "great responsibility for the solution of the Kosovo
problem," his press secretary said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dmitry Yakushkin told reporters that the decision to shorten
the visit was made during Yeltsin's flight to Alma-Ata from
Tashkent, where he just finished a two-day state visit.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has been suffering from a cold since Sunday. According
to Yakushkin, he made the decision upon the doctor's insistence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yeltsin has been closely following the situation in
Kosovo and talked to Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov during the
flight from Tashkent.
</P>
<P>
Yakushkin said that Yeltsin's stay in Kazakhstan was cut short
"only in formal terms," as the working part of the schedule will
be implemented.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and his Kazahk counterpart Nursultan Nazarbayev will
sign two documents and their ministers will sign six.
</P>
<P>
According to Itar-Tass news agency, Gennady Zyuganov, leader of
the Communist faction in the State Duma, or lower house of
parliament said that Yeltsin was very ill and was "even unable to
review a guard of honor" during his visit to Tashkent.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov made the remarks at a press conference in Moscow
Monday. 
</P>
