<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Cuts Military Service Terms by 3 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced on Monday to cut
the terms of military service by three months as of October 23.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the headquarters of the Armed Forces said
the term of service will be reduced to 21 months from the current
24 months.
</P>
<P>
The period will be further reduced to 18 months for those
serving in operational regions or deprived areas, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The decision will take effect as of October 23 and remain in
place for the next four years, it added.
</P>
<P>
The statement said those who have finished 20 months of their
service in operational regions or deprived areas, and those with
23 months service in other areas will be discharged on October 23.
</P>
<P>
Iran's military is under direct control of supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who is the commander-in-chief. The Armed
Forces comprise the Army, the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps
(IRGC) and the security forces, or armed police. Both the Army and
the IRGC have their own ground, air and naval forces.
</P>
<P>
The country also has a large number of Basijis, or volunteers,
who are usually under the command of the IRGC.
</P>
<P>
It is not immediately known why Iran take this move. In the
ongoing standoff with Afghan Taliban militia, Iran has massed more
than 250,000 troops along the border and carried out military
exercises.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban killed 12 Iranian diplomats and a journalist in
August when its militants run over the northern opposition
stronghold of Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Tehran demands the extradition and trial of the killers, return
of the remaining bodies of slain Iranians and an apology from the
Taliban, as pre-conditions for a peaceful solution of the crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
