<HEADLINE> Italian Cabinet Meets On NATO's Use of Its Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Italy's outgoing cabinet met
Monday morning to decide on the use of Italian air bases in any
NATO missions against Yugoslavia over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Senate decided Sunday that, although it is only supposed to
take care of day-to-day business, the government that lost a
confidence vote on Friday can still implement international
accords on NATO's use of military bases in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Bases in eastern Italy have played a major role in NATO actions
in the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
But the Senate ruled that parliamentary approval is required in
order to commit Italy to providing men and aircraft or even
logistic support for possible NATO strikes against Serb targets in
Yugoslavia's rebel province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
United States Envoy Richard Holbrooke is still trying to get
Serbia and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to accept a
NATO-Russian multinational peace force in Kosovo that would lift
the threat of military action.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels Monday, the 16 NATO member countries are expected
to transfer authority for intervention in Kosovo to supreme
commander of allied forces in Europe, U.S. General Wesley Clark.
</P>
<P>
The decision has to be unanimous; only Germany, Portugal and
Italy has yet to give the thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
France was reported Monday morning to be prepared to supply 40
or so planes for air actions against the Serb forces involved in
military conflicts in the independence-minded ethnic Albanian
province.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo leaders Sunday night voiced skepticism on the
possibility of Holbrooke's talks producing anything constructive,
claiming that Milosevic "only understands force". 
</P>
</TEXT>
