<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Copper Mines Survival Plan to Fail: Citibank  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- A survival plan to improve the
performance of the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) is
international credit markets, Citibank has predicted.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Monday quoted the lastest Treasury Letter
released by Citibank at the weekend as saying that Zambia's
conglomerate is likely to encounter difficulties in raising
credit due to its low credit standing internationally, and the
ZCCM Survival Plan announced last month could not be carried out.
</P>
<P>
The plan, unveiled by a task team comprising representatives
from the Zambian government, Bank of Zambia, Zambia Copper
Investment and ZCCM, aims at placing the country's largest
traditional foreign exchange earner on an improved financial
footing and accelerating the privatization of the company's
remaining assets.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the factors that are likely to weigh heavily
against ZCCM's ability to raise incremental credit include
adverse effects of the ongoing privatization process,
deterioration in operating performance and poor international
demand conditions.
</P>
<P>
It is likely that the donors would continue withholding their
pledged balance of payment support for Zambia if the survival
plan flops, said the bank in the letter.
</P>
<P>
With the failure of the plan, the bank predicts that problems
of poor employee morale, inadequate raw material supplies and
unsufficient working capital which have a direct and adverse
impact on the conglomerate's output will persist.
</P>
<P>
The negative impact on productivity, said the letter, will
accelerate with the longer it takes to privatize ZCCM's two
largest mines, Nkana and Nchanga, which account for 65 percent of
the company's total production.
</P>
<P>
ZCCM's copper production figure for September at 29,601 tons
was two percent below those in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
