<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Get Aid From WB, IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Minister of Finance
A.M.S. said Monday his government will get emergency assistance
from the World Bank (WB) and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF), particularly for balance of payment support to meet import
needs.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh will get 200 million U.S. dollars from the WB as
post-flood rehabilitation emergency aid and 130 million dollars
from the IMF for balance of payment support to meet import needs,
in accordance with agreements to be signed with two institutions
within this month or next month, he told a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister returned to Dhaka Sunday from Washington
where he participated in the annual conference of the WB and IMF,
and held talks with high-level officials of the two financial
agencies.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government has appealed to the donor countries
and international agencies for about 880 million dollars of
emergency assistance for post-flood rehabilitation work.
</P>
<P>
Until October 7, Bangladesh had received commitments of 212.8
million dollars from organizations and governments of 41 countries
to support its effort to help the flood victims, according to
Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad.
</P>
<P>
The most severe flooding in a century in Bangladesh had gripped
about two-thirds of the country for 10 weeks and affected about
half its 127 million people, with nearly 30 million of them hit
seriously, leaving over 1,000 dead and inflicting a preliminary
estimated loss of around 4.3 billion dollars. 
</P>
