<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Disasters Reduce Chinese GNP Heavily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Economic losses caused by
natural disasters have reduced China's gross national product (GNP)
by some 3-6 percent annually, with the percentage continuing to
rise along with the accumulation of national wealth.
</P>
<P>
Fan Baojun, vice minister of Civil Affairs, said today that
property losses resulting from natural disasters during the
1991-1995 period amounted to 656.2 billion yuan (82.6 billion US
dollars), with average annual losses standing at 131.2 billion
yuan. The 1995 figure alone hit 288.2 billion yuan, with the level
for 1997 standing at 197.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Fan attended today's Beijing forum to mark the International
Decade For Natural Disaster Reduction and said that China is one of
the few countries in the world which suffer from annual natural
calamities which kill thousands of people, damage crops on
millions of hectares and affect over 200 million people.
</P>
<P>
This year's devastating summer flooding and various other
natural disaster killed more than 4,000 people, according to
Fan, who also serves as vice director of China Committee for the
International Decade for Natural Disaster Reduction.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has allocated over 1,000 billion yuan
over the past 50 years for disaster reduction
programs.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the overall achievements have been far from
satisfactory when compared to developed countries, said Wang
Angsheng, a professor working for the Disaster Reduction Center
under the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Wang called for the establishment of a national natural
disaster prevention network which would reduce government inputs
while substantially reduce economic losses.
</P>
<P>
A researcher with the State Seismological Bureau said China
should increase environmental protection efforts in the new
century to reduce the frequency of natural
disasters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gascoigne Urged to Admit Alcohol Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 12 (Xinhua)-- Former England boss Graham
Taylor has urged Paul Gascoigne to admit he has a drinking
problem.
</P>
<P>
The Watford manager has also revealed he had tried to help the
wayward star when he played for Lazio and during England's failed
qualifying for the 1994 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
"What Paul Gascoigne must do for his future life is stand up
and admit he has a drink problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gascoigne was admitted to a rehabilitation clinic for alcohol
and stress problems over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for his premier league side Middlesbrough said he
would not play for the club again until he is given the all-clear
from doctors at the clinic.
</P>
<P>
Middlesbrough paid Glasgow Rangers 3.5 million pounds (5.93
million U.S. dollars) for Gascoigne in March. He was dropped from
the England squad for the World Cup finals by coach Glenn Hoddle.
</P>
<P>
The latest chapter in Gascoigne's chequered career comes just
days after he was seen sporting a black eye following reports of
a three-day drinking session in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
And on Friday Gascoigne was found sobbing at a railway station
near his ex-wife's house. 
</P>
