<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Rally Violence Stage-Managed: Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Political violence at a
ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) rally Sunday was
stage-managed to convince regional powers of the need to prolong
their military intervention in Lesotho, opposition parties
claimed Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This is a ploy by the LCD to divert these governments'
attention to the current political problems," South African Press
Association (SAPA) quoted opposition alliance spokeswoman Mamello
Morrison as saying.
</P>
<P>
One person was beaten to death and two others died of severe
head injuries in hospital after the LCD meeting erupted into
chaos Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The LCD public meeting ended in chaos when LCD supporters
attacked a group of youths allegedly armed with firearms and a
bomb.
</P>
<P>
Enraged LCD supporters cornered the youths, who had
infiltrated the rally at Lerepeng, six kilometers east of Maseru.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho police commissioner Bolutu Makoaba said one of the
youths was allegedly found trying to plant a bomb at the grounds.
</P>
<P>
The LCD leadership immediately blamed opposition parties for
the incident, saying the youths were sent to assassinate Prime
Minister Pakalitha Mosisili and his deputy, Kelebone Maope.
</P>
<P>
Morrison said Monday that the alliance knew nothing about an
assassination plot.
</P>
<P>
If the youths were from the opposition, she said, they could
have gone to the rally of their own accord.
</P>
<P>
"We never authorized any assassinations. If it is true that
these boys are our members then the leadership of the alliance
would like to disassociate itself with their action," Morrison
said.
</P>
<P>
Maope Monday still insisted the youths were sent by the
opposition alliance.
</P>
<P>
"These people need to be a little bit more serious because we
were nearly killed there yesterday (Sunday)."
</P>
<P>
South Africa continued its behind-the-scenes mediation
Monday.
</P>
<P>
South African safety and security minister, Sydney Mufamadi,
was meeting delegations of the rival parties at an undisclosed
venue in South Africa in preparation for the round three of
multi-party talks in Maseru Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho government and opposition parties agreed to hold
fresh general elections in 15 to 18 months, but failed to agree
on who should run the country during this period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
