<HEADLINE> Malaysia Vows to Enhance Trade Despite Downturn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Monday vowed to
continue with its policy of enhancing its level of external trade
although the country is facing an economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said Malaysia would
continue to look for opportunities and investments with its
foreign partners as this could reduce the pressure from financial
and economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Through this policy, Malaysia recorded a trade surplus of 6.3
billion ringgit (about 1.657 billion U.S. dollars) in August and
the local industrial sector also managed to continue their
operations, he said at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said, "Although the economic situation is not as good
as before, Malaysia is prepared to receive investments and enhance
economic relations with its foreign trading partners."
</P>
<P>
He said the government had implemented several measures
including selective exchange controls and providing opportunities
to foreign investors to evaluate and plan their investments in the
country.
</P>
<P>
He said local investors were also aided by the fixed peg of the
ringgit at 3.80 to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government is confident that foreign
investors' interest in Malaysia would resume soon following the
implementation of several economic policies. 
</P>
