<HEADLINE> News Corp Rise Pushes Australian Stocks Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares shrugged off
firmer Japanese and Hong Kong markets Monday to close only
marginally higher, boosted by a 6-percent jump in News Corp
shares.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished 10.3 points firmer at
2,501.6, with News Corp's rise the standout.
</P>
<P>
The global media group's shares had gone into a tailspin over
the past two weeks, with a decision to pull back on the extent of
its Fox float seen as one of the leading factors behind the
selling.
</P>
<P>
The fortnight's fall saw the ordinary shares go from 11.20
Australian dollars to 8.64 before bouncing back 54.7 cents to 9.19
- in line with its trade in New York on Friday - as buyers took
advantage of the nine-month low. News Corp preferred shares added
46 cents at 8.11 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The rise in News Corp shares was linked to the better
performance of the U.S. stock market on Friday. The Dow Jones
industrial average on Friday rose 167.61 to 7,899.52, a gain of
114.83 points for the week.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the market, non-institutional interest remained
tepid as global economic uncertainty lingered and the historical
fear of October financial markets contributed to the ill-will.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, the Nikkei index jumped 5 percent on the back of new
proposals to prop up the nation's banking system.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, the key Hang Seng index closed up 483.48 points
at 8,990.27, with late profit-taking eroding earlier even more
substantial gains.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the all industrials index was up 22.2 points to
4,345.0.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank, seen as a potential acquirer of
competitors, fell 38.3 cents. The other major banks were higher,
ANZ up five cents, Westpac was 11 cents better while Commonwealth
finished 16 cents firmer.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications major Telstra dropped 12.4 cents as
uncertainty remained over how much of the company would be
privatized, while final payment of installment receipts was due in
a little over a month.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was unchanged at 1,024.6 points.
</P>
<P>
BHP was up 14 cents. It is expected that the company could be
close to announcing a new chief executive.
</P>
<P>
The gold index fell 38.4 points to 1,212.6 as the bullion price
lost 1.80 U.S. dollars per ounce to 297.30.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 275.24 million shares at a value of 946.80 million
Australian dollars (587.02 million U.S. dollars), with 544 falls,
494 rises and 388 steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
