<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of S. Korea's HIV Carriers Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 12 (Xinhua) -- An additional 33 people in South
Korea were found carrying the AIDS-causing virus in the third
quarter of the year, the Health and Welfare Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The more recent discovery brought the total number people
tested positive for the deadly human immunedeficiency virus (HIV)
to 844 in the country as of the end of September.
</P>
<P>
Among the 844 HIV carriers, nearly 70 percent were in their 20s
and 30s, and men outnumbered women by a margin of seven to one.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter, 12 HIV carriers developed into the
full-blown acquired immune deficiency syndrome (AIDS) and 15
others died of the killer disease.
</P>
<P>
The nation has seen the number of HIV infection cases double in
the past five years. In 1994, the number stood at only 413.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said 95 percent of those found HIV-positive in the
country contracted the virus through sexual contact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
