<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Housing Bank to Be Privatized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Government Housing
Bank will soon be privatized as part of a move to streamline the
banking sector, the Thai News Agency (TNA) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first government-owned bank to be privatized
since Thailand took strides in reforming its ailing financial
sector following the financial crisis that erupted in July last
year.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet will consider a bill to privatize the bank when it
convenes later this week, the report quoted a Finance Ministry
source as saying.
</P>
<P>
Once privatized, the bank's capital will be converted into
shares valued at 10 baht each (about 0.26 U.S. dollar at current
exchange rate).
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry will be the major shareholder of the bank
in the initial stage, until the cabinet approves share transfers
to private partners.
</P>
<P>
Under the privatization bill, the bank will also be allowed to
expand its activities from loans on houses to those on furniture
and other kinds of household decorations.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry will guarantee such loans, the amount of
which will not exceed 12 times as much as paid-up shares of the
bank.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has closed 52 financial institutions and
taken over nearly 10 commercial banks in a sweeping reform aimed
at spurring an economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
The move to privatize the Government Housing Bank is seen as a
step-up of the privatization process in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
