<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of activists from
Jammu and Kashmir Democratic Freedom Party (JKDFP) held a
demonstration Monday outside the United Nations office here
demanding inclusion of Kashmiris in the scheduled talks between
India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
JKDFP chief spokesman Riaz Khewar said that the party was ready
to act as a bridge between the two neighboring countries to narrow
down their differences over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The vexed Kashmir issue would solved by the people of Jammu and
Kashmir themselves and nobody could speak on their behalf, Khewar
said at the rally.
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan agreed last month to resume the foreign
secretary-level talks in Islamabad in November to discuss disputes
between the two countries including Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The party's president Shabir Ahmed Shah submitted a memorandum
to the UN office, which urged both India and Pakistan to stop
nuclear race and sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
The memorandum, addressed to UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
claimed that the people of Jammu and Kashmir through their true
representatives could work out a formula which would solve the
issue once for all.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to step into next millennium with prosperity and
peace," shah said after submitting the memorandum. 
