<HEADLINE> Russia Recalls Envoys to NATO for Consultations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Russia has recalled its
ambassador to Belgium and permanent representative to NATO Sergei
Kislyak for consultations on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
Also back in Moscow, as reported Monday by the Interfax news
agency, was military representative to NATO Viktor Zavarzin.
</P>
<P>
The move is believed to be related to the Russian government's
strong objection to the Western military alliance's threatened air
strikes on Yugoslavia over the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The duration of the representatives' stay in Moscow will depend
on the circumstances, Vladimir Chizhov, director of the Third
European Department in charge of the Balkans in the Russian
Foreign Ministry, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the representatives for consultations is "quite usual
diplomatic practice," Chizhov said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO council meeting in Brussels scheduled for late Monday
to discuss plans for a military operation in Yugoslavia does not
seem to be the final step towards the operation, Chizhov said.
</P>
<P>
Russia is continuing to act vigorously for peaceful resolution
of the Kosovo problem.
</P>
<P>
Russia, which has repeatedly vented its opposition to NATO
strikes against Yugoslavia, said that any NATO force used there
without U.N. mandate would undermine the entire system of current
international relations.
</P>
<P>
Many Russian officials have warned that the NATO strikes, if
implemented, would make Moscow reconsider its cooperation with the
trans-Atlantic alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
