<HEADLINE> Quakes Damage 239 Buildings in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- A total of 239 buildings and
public facilities in Donggala district in Indonesia's Central
Sulawesi province were damaged in two consecutive tectonic
earthquakes Sunday, according to Antara News Agency Monday.
</P>
<P>
The earthquakes registered 5.5 and 6.1 respectively on the
Richter scale, Secretary of the Donggala District Administration
Ahmad Abdul Rauf said.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorology and Geophysics Body reported that the epicenter
was at some 16 kilometers northwest of Palu, capital of the
province.
</P>
<P>
Rauf said the damage was done to state elementary and senior
high schools and markets.
</P>
<P>
In Palu city, 12 buildings were heavily and 51 lightly damaged.
</P>
<P>
Most of the damaged public and residential buildings were
permanent and semi-permanent structures. But they were generally
quite old and thus easily affected by violent earth movements.
</P>
<P>
Rauf said the figures he had given were not yet final as social
workers were still collecting data in the field.
</P>
<P>
The social service and the Indonesian Red Cross of Donggala
district had already distributed one ton of rice, 40 dozen packs
of instant noodles and one bag of sugar among people affected by
the earthquakes, Rauf added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
