<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Japan to Discuss Aid Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda said Monday he will
head a delegation to Japan for talks on obtaining the funds.
</P>
<P>
The package was proposed by Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa last week at the annual meetings of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
About half the money is expected to be in the form of medium-
and long-term loans issued through the Export-Import Bank of
Japan. The rest will come as short-term financing to support
trade.
</P>
<P>
The package would help provide liquidity to Asian countries at
a time when international capital markets were all but closed to
sovereign and corporate borrowers, Tarrin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's sovereign bond maturing in 2007 now trades at 6.75-7
percentage points above U.S. treasuries, compared with a spread of
0.9 points at the time of issue in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
Spreads on all emerging market debt have jumped sharply in the
past year as investors demand higher premiums to cover increased
risks.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government earlier this year approved borrowing up to
5 billion dollars in overseas funds to bolster domestic liquidity
and supplement public spending programs to spur the economy.
</P>
<P>
Plans had called for the issue of up to 2 billion dollars in
Yankee bonds, but difficult market conditions have caused Thai
officials to shelve the plans and consider alternatives, such as
syndicated loans or issuing yen-denominated "Samurai" bonds.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said foreign funds were still needed to supplement
increased public sector spending to stimulate domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand and other Southeast Asian representatives
attending the IMF-World Bank meetings warmly welcomed the Japanese
initiative.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
