<HEADLINE> Greek PM on Settlement of Kosovo Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTALYA, TURKEY, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister
Costas Simitis said Monday that peace and stability in the Balkan
region will face disaster if the Kosovo issue cannot be solved
soon.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the first day meeting of the Balkan summit held in
the southern Turkish resort city, Simitis said that the tensions
in Kosovo threaten stability in the region and can destroy the
fragile peace in the Yugoslav Federation.
</P>
<P>
"The humanitarian crisis would have disastrous consequences for
all our countries and put an abrupt end to economic development,"
Simitis said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the other Balkan nations to make joint efforts to
help solve the Kosovo issue because they are most affected by the
crisis and by punitive measures of the international community.
</P>
<P>
Simitis said that Greece, which is both a NATO and EU member,
will do its utmost to play a positive part in easing tensions in
the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Although NATO has warned that it will launch air strikes to
drive the Yugoslav forces out of Kosovo, Athens said that all
diplomatic means should be tried before taking military action.
</P>
<P>
Greece fears that a NATO military strike against Yugoslavia
would intensify armed conflicts in Kosovo and further produce
negative impacts on other Balkan countries, including Greece
itself.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech at the meeting, Macedonian Prime Minister
Branko Crvenkovski said that his country supports an immediate
settlement of the Kosovo issue with political means and by way
of negotiations and dialog.
</P>
<P>
Crvenkovski stressed that the Kosovo crisis should be solved
within the framework of fully respecting the territorial
integrity of Yugoslavia and human rights of all nationalities in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Croatian Deputy Foreign Minister Ivo Sanader and
Bosnian Ambassador to Turkey Besim Spahic, who are present at the
summit as observers, expressed the hope that the Balkan summit
would make a contribution to the settlement of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
