<HEADLINE> Uzbekistan, Russia Steps up Economic, Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
capped a two-day state visit to Uzbekistan Monday with agreements
calling for closer economic and security cooperation and peace in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and his Uzbek counterpart, Islam Karimov, also signed a
Russia-Uzbekistan-Tajikistan declaration on military assistance if
either one is attacked.
</P>
<P>
Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov had signed the trilateral
document earlier.
</P>
<P>
Under the declaration, the signatories will "develop dialogue
and cooperation in the field of security and defense on the
principles of equality and partnership."
</P>
<P>
The three countries will cooperate in coordination with the
United Nations, the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE) and the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) and
interested countries "for full political stabilization in
Tajikistan," the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The signatories vow to work "for international peace,
stability and security on the regional and global scale by
supporting one another in every way, above all in preventing
threats to their sovereignty and territorial integrity."
</P>
<P>
Under the document, if one of the signatory countries believes
there is a threat to its security, territorial integrity and
sovereignty or to regional peace and security, the three countries
will immediately hold trilateral consultations directly or through
the international organizations where they are members to take
steps to avert the threat.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said the trilateral mutual aid declaration "is open to
other states."
</P>
<P>
On Afghanistan, Yeltsin and Karimov urged the Taliban movement
and other influential groups in the Asian country to hold
constructive dialogue for the sake of maintaining Afghan statehood
and assuring a lasting peace and revival, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Hostilities must stop immediately, and other countries must
cease supplies of military hardware to any party in the Afghan
conflict, the two presidents said in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
They believe that the fratricidal war in Afghanistan is
continuing mainly because the Talibans have been acted in flagrant
defiance of U.N. resolutions, stressing that escalation of
fighting there may lead to serious negative consequences for
Central Asian countries and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin pointed to the need "to use political potential more
effectively for achieving peace and stability in the southern
flanks of the CIS."
</P>
<P>
The two sides also signed a number of documents on cooperation
in telecommunications, culture and protection of computer software.
</P>
<P>
"Islam Karimov and I definitely spoke for closer foreign
economic, political and military-technical cooperation," Yeltsin
said Monday after the signing of Russian-Uzbek agreements in
Tashkent.
</P>
<P>
Karimov, for his part, stressed "the important stabilizing role
of Russia in Central Asia" and Yeltsin's firm and principled
stance "as an advocate of equal and mutually beneficial
cooperation between Uzbekistan and Russia."
</P>
<P>
"Together we stand for peaceful settlement of the conflict in
Afghanistan and restoration of stability in Tajikistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has left Tashkent and arrived in Alma-Ata, Kazakhstan,
on the second and final leg of his Central Asia tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
