<HEADLINE> Turkey Calls for Peaceful Solution to Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTALYA, TURKEY, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz Monday called on the Balkan leaders to make joint
efforts for a peaceful settlement of the current Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the two-day Balkan summit here, Yilmaz said that
the armed conflicts in the Yugoslav province is posing a serious
threat to the regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis in Kosovo causes deep concern regionally and
internationally. A durable and viable solution needs to be found
as soon as possible, needless to say, by peaceful means," Yilmaz
said.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz stressed that all legitimate rights of all inhabitants
of Kosovo should be respected within a fair and democratic
constitutional system.
</P>
<P>
NATO has threatened to launch air strikes against the Yugoslav
military targets if the Yugoslav government still refuses to
withdraw its troops from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a NATO member, has agreed to play a role in the
possible NATO mission in that region, making Belgrade unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
On the current turmoil in Albania, Yilmaz said that Turkey is
very much concerned about the situation in the Balkan nation.
</P>
<P>
New and constructive initiatives must be worked out to help
Albania restore democracy and constitutional order, the Turkish
prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered at the Balkan summit, Romanian Prime
Minister Radu Vasile said that his country supports the joint
efforts of the international community aimed at preventing further
deterioration of the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Vasile, however, said that Romania would not assume a direct
participation in military operations against Yugoslavia that
might be launched by NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
