<HEADLINE> U.N., Taliban Hold Third Round of Talks in Islamabad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.N. Envoy on
Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi and the Taliban delegation held their
third round of talks here Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
During the talks the two sides further dilated on their
respective positions on all aspects of their discussion, said
official sources.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Secretary General of the Organization of Islamic
Conference Ibrahim Baker also attended the talks, according to the
sources.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi and Wakeel Ahmed Mutawakil, senior advisor to Taliban
leader Mohammad Omar, held two sessions of talks Sunday, but their
talks ended with no headway.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy is on a visit to the region following the Six
Plus Two meeting in New York on September 21, which had called for
despatching the Secretary General's Envoy on Afghanistan for a
peaceful end to standoff between Iran and the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Before flying here Thursday night, Brahimi spent four days in
Teheran as part of his peace mission last week and invited the
Taliban militia to Islamabad for talks on the Afghanistan
situation.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban on their part had invited the U.N. official to
visit Afghanistan but Brahimi had not undertaken the trip to the
war-shattered country citing security reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
