<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passage of Banking Bills Sends Share Prices Up in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The long-awaited enactment of a
set of banking-reform bills injected confidence into the Tokyo
stock market Monday and boosted the Nikkei index by 5.24 percent.
</P>
<P>
Following the move by the Diet, or parliament, the Nikkei Stock
Average of 225 selected issues on the First Section of the Tokyo
Stock Exchange surged 675.04 points to close at 13,555.01.
</P>
<P>
It was the year's fourth largest single-day points gain.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all First Section
issues, advanced 40.84 points, or 4.16 percent, to 1,023.34.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section was heavy at about 570 million
shares, slightly down from 581.84 million shares Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Bank shares, as a sector, soared 8.01 percent on prospects that
a much larger-than-expected amount of public money would be pumped
into major lenders to help ease the current credit crunch.
</P>
<P>
The strong gains were the result of the new legislation, deemed
by investors as a signal of the government's desire to prevent
Japan's biggest banks from collapsing, traders said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the sharp rebound on the Wall Street, of the
United States, on Friday helped restore some confidence in Japan's
battered big-name exporter shares.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,337 issues listed on the First Section at the Tokyo
market, gainers outpaced losers 966 to 196, with 115 issues ending
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
