<HEADLINE> Yugoslav PM: Kosovo Issue Brooks No Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTALYA, TURKEY, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Prime
Minister Momir Bulatovic said here Monday that the Kosovo issue
is a domestic question and brooks no military intervention by
foreign powers.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the first day meeting of the Balkan summit held in
southern Turkish port city of Antalya, Bulatovic stressed that
attempts are being made by certain countries to "create
artificial tensions" in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
"NATO (North Atlantic Treaty Organization) threats of military
intervention are unacceptable, absolutely counterproductive and
cannot resolve anything, but can only contribute to
destabilization of the region with unforeseeable consequences,"
Bulatovic said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the military action that might be launched by
Western countries is aimed at furthering disintegrating the
Yugoslav Federation.
</P>
<P>
"Human rights, the rights of nations and national minorities
were abused for the purposes of particular separatist or
hegemonic interests," he added.
</P>
<P>
With regard to regional cooperation, the Yugoslav prime
minister said that his country has always pursued an active
policy of good neighborly relations and comprehensive equitable
cooperation with all its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Bulatovic met with his Turkish counterpart Mesut Yilmaz Sunday
afternoon, but did not speak to reporters about the outcome of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic also stressed
Sunday that the Kosovo crisis should be solved through political
means under the principles of the United Nations Charter.
</P>
<P>
However, NATO has warned that air strikes will be inevitable
unless the Yugoslav administration agrees to pull its forces out
of the Kosovo region.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a NATO member, has decided to participate in a possible
NATO peacekeeping mission aimed at ending the armed conflicts in
the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Prime ministers from Greece, Romania, Bulgaria, Macedonia,
Yugoslavia as well as Turkey will try to find a solution to help
solve the Kosovo crisis during the two-day summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian delegation is headed by Foreign Minister Paskal
Milo as the Albanian premier is not able to come to the summit
because of the continuing turmoil in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
