<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 09:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Foundation Raises Award on Rushdie Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Khordad 15 Foundation
has decided to increase its award for killing British writer
Salman Rushdie, the Jomhuri Islami (Islamic Republic) daily
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The foundation's head, Ayatollah Sheikh Hassan Sanai, announced
on Sunday in Mashhad, northeastern province of Khorasan that his
foundation would add a sum of 300,000 U.S. dollars to its
2.5-million-dollar award.
</P>
<P>
Sanai, a representative of Iran's Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei, said the recent western propaganda was "trying to cast a
shadow" over late Iranian Supreme Leader Ayatollah Khomeini's 1989
fatwa, or religious decree, calling on the world Muslims to kill
Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
The foundation offered the award soon after Khomeini published
the fatwa against Rushdie for his controversial novel "the Satanic
Verses" considered to have insulted the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Hezbollah Students Association also announced recently
an award of 1 billion Iranian rials (about 333,000 dollars) for
carrying out the death sentence on Rushdie after the Iranian
government promised not to implement Khomeini's fatwa.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said last month in New
York that the Iranian government would not take or support any
actions to threaten the life of Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
He said the award offered by the Khordad 15 Foundation has
nothing to do with the government, which does not back the move.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Britain have agreed to upgrade their diplomatic
relations to the ambassadorial level after putting aside the
Rushdie issue, a step viewed by the west as Iran's retreat from
its original stance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
