<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Upper House OKs Bank Reform Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Councillors, the
upper house of parliament, enacted Monday a set of banking reform
bills designed to fix the country's ailing banking sector.
</P>
<P>
The enactment ended months of political wrangling between the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and opposition groups led by
the Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ) over how to handle Japanese
banks' massive bad loan problem.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very grateful to see the bills become law following
negotiations among the parties," Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi also hoped that a separate package of bills on bank
recapitalization would be enacted soon.
</P>
<P>
The newly enacted bills, which cleared the House of
Representatives, the lower house of parliament, on October 2,
offer three options to deal with failed banks and call for a new
independent committee to share financial planning power with the
finance minister.
</P>
<P>
Under the bills, the financially troubled Long-Term Credit of
Japan is expected to become the first Japanese bank to go under
state control around October 20.
</P>
<P>
The reform bills do not specify how much public money would be
earmarked to deal with failed banks, but the LDP is considering
setting aside a total of 67 trillion yen (about 577.4 billion
U.S. dollars) to fix the banking sector, including 50 trillion yen
(430.9 billion dollars) for helping capital-short banks.
</P>
<P>
The LDP scheme is roughly based on a proposal put forward by
the opposition DPJ, which called for the use of 50 trillion yen
(430.9 billion dollars) in public funds. 
</P>
