<HEADLINE> Japanese Firm Promotes Vehicle Sale in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan Direct, a Japanese auto
dealer, has earmarked a total of one billion Kwacha (about
500,000 U.S. Dollars) for the introduction of a vehicle purchase
credit scheme in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Monday quoted director Saul Radunski of the
company as saying here at the weekend that the credit facility to
be launched in three months will benefit both companies and
individuals.
</P>
<P>
Radunski said the firm has the backing of a leasing company
and one billion Kwacha will be committed to the pilot project.
</P>
<P>
An estimated five million U.S. Dollars worth of business is
expected to be achieved under the scheme, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, vehicle buyers will first pay 50 percent
down payment while the balance will be settled in six to 12
months.
</P>
<P>
Radunski said that the new scheme will cover both new and
second-hand motor vehicles and no interest will be charged on the
transactions.
</P>
<P>
The firm will further offer a one-month warranty on all
second-hand vehicles and 20,000 kilometers of 12 months guarantee
on new motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The company has 70 cars, trucks and buses on the ground in
Lusaka while another 50 units are on-route from Japan.
</P>
<P>
Japan Direct is the second company to introduce the vehicle
credit scheme in Zambia after Yeti Motors which launched a credit
scheme two months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
