<HEADLINE> Law-Enforcement Inspection of Water, Soil Conservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Buhe, vice-chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC),
recently required concerned departments at all levels to increase
their awareness on water and soil conservation and handle soil
erosion in accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
Headed by Buhe, an NPC Standing Committee team on October 1
began to conduct an inspection of water and soil conservation
in Sichuan Province on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
As the key province of China's water and soil conservation
program, Sichuan has spared no effort in implementing the law in
recent years, and put forth a series of preferential policies in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the province had brought under control a
soil erosion area of 24,000 square kilometers, 12 percent of the
province's total area suffering from soil erosion. The provincial
government also stopped the logging on October 1, and
drew up a long-term plan for water and soil conservation.
</P>
<P>
Affirming the achievements and the role of Sichuan in this
year's flood relief on the Yangtze River, Buhe required the
concerned local departments to draw up coordinated rules and
increase public awareness of water and soil conservation laws in
order to enhance the constant improvement of the environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
