<HEADLINE> Chang Wins 12th Title in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Second seed Michael Chang of
the United States signalled his return to top form when he
defeated top seed Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia 4-6, 6-1, 6-2 to
win the rain-delayed Shanghai Open tennis tournament on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It was a record 12th title for Chang in Asian ATP Tour events,
his second title for 1998.
</P>
<P>
"It's definitely significant. First of all, to win in Shanghai
is very special since I have not won here before. Playing Goran
in the final, he's been in the top 10 numberous years, to beat
him was definitely a good felling," said Chang, who levelled his
career head-to-head with Ivanisevic at 5 matches all.
</P>
<P>
The heavy conditions favored Chang. A damp mist settled on
Shanghai throughtout the day, creating a cool, humid atmosphere.
The victory marks an 11-1 record for Chang in the last month,
including titles in Boston and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"The first set was close but Goran won the key points, but in
the second there was a momentum shift and the crowd started
getting into it. There was a bit of a chanting match going on,
the Chinese versus the Crotians, and that was fun to be a part
of," said Chang.
</P>
<P>
Despite the seemingly one sided score, the match took 1 hour
and 57 minutes, with Ivanisevic having a number of break point
opportunities in the third set.
</P>
<P>
"The way I played I should go to jail," said Ivanisevic. "It's
a different part of the world to be in, it was a good week but
I'm not happy with the way I played. I can beat some guys, but as
soon as I play someone tougher, I struggle."
</P>
<P>
In the doubles final, second seeds Mahesh Bhupathi and Leander
Paes won the title by stunning top seeded Todd Woodrigde and Mark
Woodforde of Australia in a gripping two hours and 46 minutes
final 6-4, 6-7(7-2), 7-6 (7-4).
</P>
<P>
The Indian's victory over the Woodies was their first win in
four attempts. 
</P>
