<HEADLINE> Former Poor Area Operates China's Largest Markets (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Taihe County is unknown to the
majority of Chinese, but it is deemed as the Capital of Pharmacy
by local pharmaceutical manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
"The Taihe pharmaceutical market is the largest of its kind in
China," says Xie Yufa, a local government official. "Therefore, we
have invested heavily in infrastructure and tried strenuous efforts
to protect it."
</P>
<P>
The recent reports about substandard medicine which were
donated to flood-hit areas have led to the close-down of a number
of stalls in the Taihe market.
</P>
<P>
"We'll put stricter restrictions on the management so as to
turn down those illegally profiteering firms," says Xie.
</P>
<P>
The pharmaceutical market is merely one of the many big markets
in Fuyang City, in east China's Anhui Province, which used to be
one of the poorest areas in the country due to frequent floods and
droughts.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two decades, local people have tried every means
to make their own fortune. But it was only known as one of the
major labor-exporting places until the early 1990s, when a number of
specialized market emerged there.
</P>
<P>
These markets include some nationally largest ones dealing in
decorating wood-plates, peppermint, cattle and animal skins and
hides, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
