<HEADLINE> Former Poor Area Operates China's Largest Markets (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Local governments at different levels have tried hard to
improve the business environment. A government official from
Fuyang says, "Local rickshaw drivers never bargain much for a
higher price, because they know it would scare away visiting
businessmen."
</P>
<P>
Local authorities often check up in the markets to see if there
are irregular activities such as illegal charges or levies
collected by government officials or other local people.
</P>
<P>
In Taihe, to protect businessmen from robbery, large quantities
of uniformed or plain-clothed policemen are deployed around
market-places, banks and post offices. "No robbery has been
reported here, though lots of business people here are moving
around with cash," says a local police officer.
</P>
<P>
With the effective and powerful support from the government,
local markets and businesses have been flourishing. Li Wenbin, who
owns one of the country's largest nylon rope and net factories, is
now further expanding his business. Recently, he has purchased two
PII 586 computers to modernize the management.
</P>
<P>
The booming markets have also milked local service
sectors. Local Hui residents have opened many Muslim restaurants
to cater to transients from across the country and even other
parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Farmers at Balihe Town, Yinshang County, have turned a country
place into a scenic holiday resort, a miniature of the Summer
Palace in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"We have copyed the scenes from wall calendars," says Zhang
Jiawang, a town leader. 
</P>
</TEXT>
