<HEADLINE> Death Toll at Lesotho Ruling Party Rally Rises to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Two more people have died
in a hospital in Maseru, the capital of Lesotho, following the
outbreak of violence Sunday at a Lesotho Congress for Democracy
(LCD) rally, and bringing the death toll to three.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the latest death report, one person was beaten to
death and four others injured when they were allegedly found
trying to plant a bomb at the rally site, South African Press
Association reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Enraged LCD supporters cornered the unidentified people after
one of them fired a shot, wounding an LCD supporters in a knee.
The LCD public meeting with the participation of 5,000 people
ended in chaos.
</P>
<P>
The LCD leaders blamed the opposition parties for sending the
people to assassinate Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili and his
deputy Kelibone Maope, who were participating in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Both Mosisili and Maope were whisked away from the rally
shortly after the violence broke out at the rally site, about six
km east of Maseru.
</P>
<P>
The LCD rally, to brief supporters on Southern African
Development Community (SADC)-initiated talks aimed at resolving
the political crisis in the kingdom, was the first to be held by
the LCD since the SADC's military intervention beginning on
September 22.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho has been in political crisis when opposition parties
claimed that the May 23 general election was rigged in favor of
the LCD.
</P>
<P>
The LCD and the opposition party alliance are due to hold the
third round talks, chaired by the South African Safety and
Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi Wednesday.  
</P>
