<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seventh East Asia Economic Summit Opens in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Seventh East Asia
Economic Summit opened here Monday with a discussion on economic
outlook for Asia.
</P>
<P>
Most speakers expressed their belief at the gathering of some
800 participants Monday morning that East Asia's sound economic
fundamentals will provide good prospects for the region.
</P>
<P>
Lee Tsao Yuan, director of the Institute of Policy Study of
Singapore, said the economic fundamentals, which are the basis for
the Asian economic miracles in the past decades, remain sound,
referring to the infrastructure, the investments, the technical
transfer, the high saving rates, the education and the strategy
for opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
These factors have not disappeared and they will benefit Asian
economic recovery and economic development in future, she said.
</P>
<P>
Citing the current trend toward stability in Asian currencies
and increasing export volumes in some Asian economies, she said
the downturn of East Asian economy seems to have touched the
bottom and is reversing its course and going toward recovery.
</P>
<P>
Charles Powell, director of the Jardine Matheson of the United
Kingdom, expressed similar idea.
</P>
<P>
He said if Asian economies enhance efficiency in manipulating
capitals, strengthen financial supervision and increase
transparency, these fundamentals will bring recovery to East Asian
economies.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized that national cohesion and strong national
leadership are decisive factors for a country to overcome its
economic woes and achieve stable and fast economic development.
</P>
<P>
While East Asia should build up confidence in itself, he said,
it also needs help from the U.S. and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Ways in which Asian economies achieve recoveries are different
from country to country, he noticed, saying it is impossible for a
single pair of shoes to fit all feet.
</P>
<P>
However, Clyde Prestowits, president of the Economic Strategy
Institute of the U.S., presented a different view. He attributed
the Asian economic crisis to too fast economic growth, the high
saving rate and high export rate and neglect of regulations and
laws in their economies.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the world will face economic recession and
plunge into more difficulties in years 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Seventh East Asia Economic Summit is organized by the
Switzerland-based World Economic Forum in partnership with the
Economic Development Board of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The summit will last for three days to end Wednesday. Singapore
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong and Philippine President Joseph
Estrada will make keynote speeches Monday evening and Tuesday
respectively .
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Commerce Supachai
Panitchpakdi of Thailand, Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
Foreign Affairs Nguyen Manh Cam of Vietnam, Vice Minister of
Finance Lou Jiwei of China, Secretary of Trade and Industry Chau
Tak Hay of Hong Kong and Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Monetary
Authority Joseph Yam will deliver their speeches at the plenary
sessions.
</P>
<P>
Attending the three-day summit are about 1,000 participants
from the member companies of the World Economic Forum worldwide
and government officials, business leaders, public figures,
leading commentators, opinion makers and experts from Asia, Europe
and North America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
