<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Capital Cracks Down On Illegal Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Facing a recent surge in
crime, Phnom Penh municipality decided to take tough measures to
crack down on illegal weapons, according to an announcement from
the municipality here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Beginning November 1, local officials and police are to go door
to door to ask residents if they have any illegal weapons and
explosives. Those who have the weapons, including state
institutions, factories, businesses, and people's residences, must
have gun licenses, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
All illegal weapons and explosives found will be confiscated
and the violators will be charged in court. But a leading official
police will only enter houses and search when they get enough
evidence.
</P>
<P>
"This is the best way to prevent random shooting and ensure
public security in the city, and I am sure the plan will have the
support and cooperation of the residents," the official said.
</P>
<P>
He expected the plan to reduce the number of illegal weapons
and explosives in the city by 70 percent. From now until November
1, the municipality will offer cash rewards for anyone who turns
in weapons or explosives to commune or district authorities.
</P>
<P>
Since October 1, police have reported at least 15 robberies or
assaults against foreigners in the capital. In addition,
kidnappings of Cambodian and Chinese-Cambodian businessmen
continue to be a major problem.
</P>
<P>
From now on, the police said, they will step up patrols in the
city at night and crack down on teenage gangs, the group police
blame for the robberies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0152 </DOCNO>
