<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 08:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Balkan Summit Discusses Kosovo Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTALYA, TURKEY, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from the
Balkan countries met here Monday moring to discuss the tense
situation in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The summit meeting was closed to the press and the discussion
is to focus on the Kosovo situation which has quickly deteriorated
due to a NATO warning that air strikes might be launched to force
the Yugoslav troops out of the region.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic reiterated Sunday
after a meeting with his Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem that the
Kosovo issue is an internal affair of Yugoslavia and brooks no
foreign military intervention.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and his Yugoslav
counterpart Momir Bulatovic left a 30-minute meeting Monday
without saying anything to the press, signaling a bad talk.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which is a NATO member, has decided to participate in a
possible NATO air strike against the Yugoslav military targets
aimed at stopping bloody conflicts in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Prime ministers from Greece, Romania, Bulgaria, Macedonia,
Yugoslavia as well as Turkey will try to find a solution to help
Belgrade avert an imminent military strike during the two-day
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian delegation is headed by Foreign Minister Paskal
Milo as the Albanian premier is not able to come to the summit
because of the continuing turmoil in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
