<HEADLINE> Rats Run Rampant in Eastern Tanzanian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Rampant rats have
invaded an area in eastern Tanzania, eating maize, beans and
cotton, unleashing fears that local people could face a hunger
crisis.
</P>
<P>
More than 55 percent of maize and beans farms in Umba
Division in the eastern Tanzanian region of Tanga, have been
damaged by the rats, local officials have told a Charles Kagonji,
a member of parliament who made a recent tour to the area.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports Monday, all the four wards in the
division -- Mnazi, Mbaramo, Lunguza and Mlalo -- have been
affected by devastating rats, Divisional Secretary Amiri Mganga
said.
</P>
<P>
Umba, with a population of some 26,000, have 700 hectares of
maize, rice, coffee and cotton.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, rats are ravaging farms in 300 villages in the
Lindi Region on the southeast coast. An anti-rodent squad said
that a hectare has some 600 rats, but efforts to control them
have been hampered due to lack of lorries to transport maize as
bait for killings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
