<HEADLINE> Development Zones in Hebei Province Play Big Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Economic development zones
in north China's Hebei Province now serve as locomotives for the
region's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Hebei has now constructed 21 development zones, 19 of which are
economic and technological development zones, the other two new
and high-tech zones. These zones generated 12.9 billion yuan in
industrial sales in the first nine months of this year, up 27
percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Their combined exports totaled 520 million U.S. dollars, 35
percent more than the figure a year ago, said Shi Rongyao,
director of the Provincial Opening-Up Office.
</P>
<P>
These development zones invested 4.2 billion yuan in
infrastructure in the first three quarters this year, and signed
1,158 contracts on the establishment of foreign-funded enterprises
involving 3.3 billion U.S. dollars in overseas investment,
one-third of the province's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Eximbank Issues Bonds Through Public Bidding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The China Export-Import Bank
(Eximbank) issued three billion yuan worth of two-year financial
bonds today, the first set of bonds the bank has ever floated
through public bidding.
</P>
<P>
Executive Vice-President of Eximbank Zhu Degui said that the
bonds first go to underwriters through public bidding, and
commercial banks and insurance companies will then buy the bonds
from the underwriters.
</P>
<P>
Previously, Eximbank's financial bonds were distributed by the
central bank to other banks and postal savings institutions, Zhu
said.
</P>
<P>
With an annual interest rate of 5.31 percent, the bonds are
expected to be traded on the national interbank money market with
approval from the central bank. Revenues from the bond issue will
be used for export-seller credit.
</P>
<P>
By the end of September, Eximbank, which was established in
July 1994, had provided credit to exporters in the amount of 49
billion yuan, and issued 28.9 billion yuan in financial bonds.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that 40 percent of the bank's funds this year will come
from public-bidding financial bond issues. With the constant
improvement of the country's capital market, Eximbank will
gradually increase the proportion of funds raised through public
bidding.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
