<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Residents Protected by Guarantee System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Some 170,000 urban and rural
residents in east China's Zhejiang Province are now covered by
the minimum living standard guarantee system.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 95 percent of Zhejiang's cities and counties have
implemented the minimum living standards guarantee system,
according to a provincial official. He said that money used as
guarantee funds totals 5.74 million yuan each month.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang first introduced the minimum living standard
guarantee system on a trial basis in the second half of 1996. The
system had spread to all parts of the province by the end of June
this year.
</P>
<P>
The minimum living standard, in monetary terms, in the urban
areas is an average monthly income of 58-165 yuan per family
member, while the figure for rural residents is 37-140 yuan,
according to the official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cancellation of Fees Reduces Enterprise Financial Burdens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The financial burden of
enterprises in this special economic zone in east China's Fujian
Province has declined steadily as more administrative fees have
been cancelled or reduced.
</P>
<P>
The municipal authorities had annulled or cut 372 types of
administrative fees by the end of May, reducing the financial
burden on enterprises by 221 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
In July this year, the city government took new
measures to further lessen the financial burden in an effort to
improve Xiamen's overall investment environment. The latest
measures are expected to cut costs to enterprises by more than 200
million yuan a year.
</P>
<P>
The city government has also decided to ban within two years
the introduction of any new administrative fees targeted at
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
