<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Seeking WB Fund for More Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is currently seeking more
fund from the World Bank (WB) to boost power generation at the Owen
Falls Dam in Jinja, some 80 kms east of the capital.
</P>
<P>
A WB team was invited to Uganda recently to assess the facilities
of Uganda Electricity Board (UEB) and to explore possible ways to
end chronic power shortages in the fast developing country, the
Nairobi-based weekly East African reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The team had looked at the possibility of providing further
funding for the dam extension project so that three more turbines
could be installed to boost power generation.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to make recommendations to the bank's headquarters in
Washington but prefered to co-fund with other donor agencies to
bring in the three machines.
</P>
<P>
UEB said Uganda is generating some 180 megawatts of
electricity while the demand tops 230 megawatts. So blackouts are
inevitable during peak hours.
</P>
<P>
A UEB official was quoted as saying that the demand for power
would continue to rise with technological development and population
growth.
</P>
<P>
Uganda had a population of 4.96 million in 1954 when the
Owen Falls Dam was built and it has shot up to more than 20 million
now.
</P>
<P>
Of power consumption, residential consumption accounted for 55
percent of the total power output. The commercial sector and industry
consume 25 and 20 percents respectively.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, the Ugandan economy has witnessed a growth rate
of 6 percent, one of the success stories for the East African region
and even the whole continent.
</P>
<P>
With further development of national economy, Uganda will face a
much bigger demand for power. When the dam extension project is
completed by 1999 as expected, some 80 megawatts of power can be
added to the power output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
