<HEADLINE> New Zealand University to Dismiss Student Defaulters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Victoria University in
Wellington, capital of New Zealand, will cancel the enrollment of
students who have not paid 1998 tuition fees and student
association levies, if debt collectors cannot recover the money,
the Dominion reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper said that about 200 students are
facing the threat of dismissal.
</P>
<P>
It quoted David Brian, finance and property director of the
university, as saying, "I think we will have to disenrol students
this year. I think it is a sad inevitability. It's the
vice-chancellor's position that we do this if we can't collect the
fees, and we're carrying that out."
</P>
<P>
Brian said the university had been sending letters to students
who owed money and followed them up with leaflets in student and
university magazines, notice boards and lecture theaters.
</P>
<P>
A "healthy number" of students had cleared fee debts in recent
weeks, cutting the amount outstanding from 1.4 million NZ dollars
(0.7 million U.S. dollars) to 740,000 NZ dollars (370,000 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the New Zealand Ministry of
Education, the total outstanding debt students owe the government
through borrowing from the student loan scheme has surpassed 2.4
billion NZ dollars (1.2 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The figure will top three billion next year and four billion by
2001.
</P>
<P>
Last week, New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley revealed
that the government is now considering paying student loans
incrementally instead of in lump sums.
</P>
<P>
She said she had found students doing things other than meeting
their course costs with their loans, such as buying and selling
shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
