<HEADLINE> China to Further Raise Train Speeds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 12 (Xinhua) -- China's railway departments
will take measures to further raise train speeds, said Chang
Guozhi, chief dispatcher of the Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
More sections of major railway lines will be fenced in, and
basic facilities including bridges, roadbeds, signals and
telecommunications will be consolidated. Fly-overs will be built
at crossings on railway lines with a speed of over 140 km per
hour, he said.
</P>
<P>
Train speeds were raised on April 1 last year and October 1
this year, and trains now run at a speed of 140-160 km per hour on
the Beijing-Shanghai, Beijing-Guangzhou and Beijing-Harbin
lines. "But there is still room for a hike of train speed," Chang
said.
</P>
<P>
China's railways are coming into an era of high speed. Work on
the Beijing-Shanghai express railway, the first of its kind in
China, will begin in the year 2000, with an estimated speed of
300 km per hour. An express train now runs on the
Guangzhou-Shenzhen line at 200 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
Chang said the increased speeds will satisfy demands
brought on by economic development and improvement in people's
living standards, and sharpen the competitive edge of railways
as compared with highways and civil aviation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
