<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Off-load 87 More State-owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
taken steps for off-loading 87 more state-owned enterprises (SOEs)
under its privatization policy, an English newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Of the enterprises, 79 have been readied for sell-out, and 21
of them are in jute sector, 19 textiles, 21 steel and engineering,
10 sugar and food and eight in chemical sector, The Independent
daily quoted officials in the Privatization Board as saying.
</P>
<P>
Steps have been taken for the disposal of shares from eight
SOEs, they said, adding that tender call for these enterprises
will be issued on completion of 35 enterprises listed earlier for
privatization.
</P>
<P>
Five of the public-sector industrial units have already been
sold out to private owners, and letters of intent have been issued
for nine others.
</P>
<P>
There are about 300 SOEs in the country, with the total value
of output accounting for about six percent of the GDP (gross
domestic product). Owing to mismanagement, corruption and
bureaucracy, the SOEs are making an enormous loss of about 568
million U.S. dollars every year, which accounts for 45 percent of
the country's total investment.
</P>
<P>
To privatize the loss-making SOEs is the Bangladeshi
government's set policy. The government set up the Privatization
Board in 1993 to expedite the process of privatization.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen SOEs were privatized during the 1993-96 period, and a
World Bank survey showed that the production and management of
most of them were improved.
</P>
<P>
Since June 1996 when the present government was formed, 32 SOEs
have been privatized.
</P>
<P>
The Privatization Board has reportedly drafted a plan of SOEs'
privatization and submitted it to the government for approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
