<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-Owned Enterprises No Longer Run Schools in Fujian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, October 12 (Xinhua) -- State-owned enterprises (SOE) in
east China's Fujian Province have shaken off the burden of running
schools for their workers' children.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the provincial economic and trade committee said
that 103 SOE-affiliated schools have been separated from SOE
beginning this autumn semester. Four more schools will become
independent from SOE in the near future.
</P>
<P>
China's SOE, known as "mini-societies," used to build
hospitals, schools, bathhouses, canteens, post offices, and houses
for their workers and staff. These responsibilities have become
heavy burdens now that they are facing difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The Fujian provincial government has worked out plans and
allocated 6.25 million yuan (about 753,000 U.S. dollars) to help
state enterprises cast off these burdens.
</P>
<P>
By separating schools from enterprises, it is believed more
funds for production and management will become
available. Besides, the schools will receive funds from local
educational bureaus to improve the quality of education.
</P>
<P>
This pilot reform, first conducted at the Nanping Textile
Mill in June 1997, proved successful and subsequently spread
throughout the province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
