<HEADLINE> India to Stage Large-scale Military Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Defense Ministry
confirmed Sunday that its army and air force were scheduled to
stage a "formation-level" exercise next month along its border
with neighboring Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The Hindustan Times daily reported Monday that the
brigade-level exercise was a "routine and a planned one" with the
participation of the Indian Air Force.
</P>
<P>
Western observers were reportedly alarmed at India's plan for
the military maneuver with 100,000 troops on its border with its
arch-enemy Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
They feared that India "might use the exercise to launch an
airstrike against a militant training camp in Pakistani Kashmir",
according to the mass circulated newspaper Sunday Telegraph
published Sunday in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Western intelligence sources as saying that
"several army divisions will mass on the sensitive border next
month for two weeks of simulated war games.
</P>
<P>
The last such exercise in 1987 had brought India and Pakistan
to the brink of an all-out war.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Telegraph said that India's short-range Prithvi
missile would be deployed for the exercises and back-up would be
provided by battleships, aircraft carriers and probably submarines
positioned off the coast of India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
However, a spokesman for the Indian Defense Ministry said
Sunday that fears of war with Pakistan were unfounded.
</P>
<P>
The talk of war was totally unfounded because India and
Pakistan informed each other of troop movement before the start of
any such exercises, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The talk of India using the exercise to launch an airstrike
for a pre-emptive strike on the Kashmir militants is baseless," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The news of military maneuver came at a sensitive time when
India and Pakistan had planned for resumption of foreign
secretary-lever talks in Islamabad next month.
</P>
<P>
According to the Sunday Telegraph, the Pakistani army might
also come up with a massive military exercise involving nuclear
weapons in the wake of India's war games in Rajasthan desert and
Arabian sea in November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
