<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sea Buckthorn Helps Ease Soil Erosion Along Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Sea buckthorn, a perennial bush
whose fruits are nowadays often used to make delicious juice, is
playing a vital role in the fight against soil erosions in the
middle and upper reaches of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Lastest figures show that a total of more than 1.15 million
hectares of sea buckthorn are grown in these areas, which suffer
some of the worst soil erosion in China.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia's Ikh Chao League pioneered the use of this shrub
tree in the anti-soil-erosion fight in the early 1980s, and this
successful experience was spread to the entire country in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 alone, the six provinces and autonomous regions of
Qinghai, Gansu, Ningxia, Shanxi, Shaanxi and Inner Mongolia
planted 55,600 hectares of sea buckthorn, which helped ease soil
erosion in areas covering more than 553 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The fruit of the shrub has been used to make juice, jam, candy,
canned fruit, medicine and beer, with the help of China's only sea
buckthorn research institute, in Youyu County, Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Last year, over 100 sea buckthorn enterprises in the middle and
upper reaches of the Yellow River produced 2,000 tons of preserved
fruit, 10,000 tons of juice and 800 tons of dried fruit,
generating an output value of 300 million yuan (36.14 million
U.S. dollars). Sea buckthorn planting and fruit processing have
also helped many poor areas escape from poverty.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
