<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Announces New Immigration Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
launched new immigration policy initiatives as part of its
Policies for Progress to attract more "highly skilled migrants" to
the country, especially from Asia.
</P>
<P>
Under the new immigration policy issued Monday by Immigration
Minister Tuariki Delamere, English language bond will be abolished
and replaced with pre-purchased English language training.
</P>
<P>
"The bond was a barrier to migration. We were missing out on
skilled migrants who could not afford the 20,000 NZ dollar (10,000
U.S. dollar) bond for their family members who did not have at
least modest English language skills," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Another important feature of the new policy is a more
realistic view of what qualifications should be accepted under the
General Skills category. Under old policy we missed out on people
with skills and expertise in a wide range of industries,
particularly high-tech, emerging industries such as information
technology.
</P>
<P>
"We will be accepting all work experience, not just experience
relevant to qualifications, for points in the General Skills
category," he said.
</P>
<P>
Delamere said the new policy has made the investor category
more streamlined, with a simpler points table and better approvals
processes to encourage those who are "willing to put down roots
and invest time and energy in developing a business" in New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The new investor category has three points categories only:
age, business experience and investor funds to replace a more
complex points system that includes points for different
categories of investments funds, qualifications and a range of
settlement factors such as spouse's qualifications and family
sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
Delamere said foreign nationals who have established successful
businesses in New Zealand can qualify for residence under the new
entrepreneur category while people interested in setting up a
business in New Zealand will be able to apply for a long-term
multiple re-entry visa to get their business underway.
</P>
<P>
The new policy also encourages foreign students who graduate
from a New Zealand tertiary institution to stay in the country, by
awarding them an extra point in the General Skills category and
waiving the requirement for them to have two years' work
experience to qualify for residence.
</P>
<P>
Delamere said the New Zealand government will open new
immigration offices in Shanghai, the largest city in China, and in
Moscow next July.
</P>
<P>
"These offices will serve General Skill category and business
migrants, but they will also play a significant role in developing
trade and tourism links with New Zealand," he said.
</P>
<P>
All regulations will take effect within less than half a year.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley issued a statement,
welcoming the launch of new immigration policy initiatives.
</P>
<P>
"The National Minority Government recognizes that increasing
the level of business expertise, investment and skilled workers in
New Zealand will assist in creating economic growth and jobs for
New Zealanders," she said.
</P>
<P>
"New Zealand must continue to present itself as a good place in
which to do business. It remains one of the best countries in the
world in which to live and bring up a family," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Rates in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
