<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slums Turned into Downtown Area in Lhasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- In Lhasa, capital of southwest
China's Tibet Autonomous Region, a slum area crowded with beggars
four decades ago has been turned into a downtown area.
</P>
<P>
In the former poor district known as Lugu near Jokhang Temple,
there are now 348 shops and restaurants and apartment buildings
for more than 1,600 residents.
</P>
<P>
Forty years ago, Lhasa had a population of about 20,000 and the
number of beggars amounted to several thousands, with most of them
living in shabby tents and shanties in Lugu.
</P>
<P>
In 1959, about 160 homeless beggars were allocated homes in the
Lugu neighborhood community after the start of democratic reform.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 40 years, the Tibet regional government has
allocated a large amount of money for adequate-housing project for
the beggars.
</P>
<P>
Today, the residents of Lhasa have an average housing floor
space of 15 square meters, and all Lugu families have moved to new
apartments with sanitary facilities.
</P>
<P>
"Since China started its reform and opening-up policy two
decades ago, Lugu District has changed a lot. The greatest change
is that people here have moved to new apartments and have begun to
lead peaceful lives," said Chugba Yungdan, a neighborhood
community official.
</P>
<P>
The community is also one of the busiest parts of Lhasa because
of its booming trade, which provides chances for local people to
gain wealth as well as buy products from all over the country.
</P>
<P>
"If you use your brain, there are many ways to get rich," says
Puncog Gungphel, offspring of the former beggars in Lugu. During
the last eight years, he has developed his business from a
teahouse to a Tibetan-style restaurant, and he also has a flour
mill and a transportation company. Now he earns about 1,000 yuan
in net profit every month.
</P>
<P>
The residents of the Lugu neighborhood community spent about
5,000 yuan per capita in 1997. At present, almost every household
has a TV set, and some have VCDs and telephones.
</P>
<P>
Lugu's changes over the past four decades are a miniature
reflection of Lhasa's development. Lhasa has expanded its area
from three square kilometers to the current 50 square kilometers,
and its population has grown from 20,000 to 130,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
