<HEADLINE> Muslim Scholars Urged to Face Challenges of New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina Sunday called on the Muslim scholars, scientists and
academicians to prepare themselves to face the challenges of the
new millennium and revive the lost glory of the Ummah, English
newspapers here reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
She made the call when addressing the 12th congregation
ceremony of the Islamic Institute of Technology (IIT) in northern
district of Gazipur.
</P>
<P>
"Once the Muslim scholars had kindled the torch of knowledge
when the entire world plunged into the darkness of ignorance and
superstition," she said, recalling the past glory of scientific
and technological achievements of the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
The IIT is a shining example of joint Islamic action and it's a
matter of great pride and honor that Bangladesh has been chosen as
the location for such a prestigious institution, she told the
function.
</P>
<P>
This year, 96 students from 15 countries were conferred
graduate and post graduate degrees from this international
institution run by the Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC)
members.
</P>
<P>
A 2.5 million U.S. dollar loan agreement has been signed with
Islamic Development Bank for the institute's second dormitory
which will be able to accommodate at least 900 students against
the present capacity of 380.
</P>
<P>
Assuring the government's continued support to the IIT, she
said the institute would grow from strength to strength.
</P>
<P>
She thanked the OIC member states which have been contributing
regularly to the IIT.
</P>
<P>
This institute is facing some financial hardships because of
mandatory contributions of 13 million dollars from some member
states, she said, appealing to all member states for contributing
to the budget as well as making generous donations to IIT.
</P>
</TEXT>
