<HEADLINE> Myanmar Launches Border Area Development Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has been launching a
number of border areas development projects in the country since
late 1988, aiming at narrowing the development gap between the
hinterland and border areas.
</P>
<P>
It started implementing a four-year development project in
1989, followed by another 11-year master plan beginning 1993 for
the development, including the first short-term three-year plan
(1993-94 to 1995-96), the first medium-term four-year plan
(1996-97 to 1999-2000) and the second medium-term four-year plan
(2000-01 to 2003-04).
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has also been cooperating with United Nations agencies
in this regard and seven projects have been or are being
implemented with the involvement of the United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) and the United Nations Drug Control Program
(UNDCP).
</P>
<P>
The government has formed the Ministry of Progress of Border
Areas and National Races and Development Affairs and the Central
Committee for Development of Border Areas and National Races to
help develop the economy, social conditions and transport of
border areas, while conserving the traditions and culture and
literature of the different nationalities.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the government has increased investment in the border
areas' development projects, spending more than 9.51 billion kyats
 (about 31.7 million U.S. dollars) so far for the projects of
building roads, bridges, hospitals, dispensaries, schools,
irrigation facilities, vocational training schools, setting up
firms, plantations, generators, TV retransmission stations and
communication links in the regions.
</P>
<P>
The 1998-99 fiscal year, which began in April, has also been
designated as the year of roads and bridges to facilitate road
links among villages and the rural and urban areas.
</P>
<P>
In order to promote the development of the border areas, the
government also gives more priority to controlling narcotic drugs.
</P>
<P>
As one of its achievements, Myanmar has been able to turn the
Mongla region in eastern Shan state into an opium-free zone and
efforts are being made to bring about more similar zones. The
country is working to totally eliminate poppy cultivation in 15
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
