<HEADLINE> Australia Announces Emergency Aid to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Australia said here Monday it
would contribute one million Australian dollars (600,000 U.S.
dollars) to United Nations' emergency relief operation for
flood-hit areas in China.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to announce that the Australian government is to
provide additional assistance to flood-devastated areas of China,"
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said the U.N. World Food Program's relief
operation, which would cost 88 million U.S. dollars, would address
the immediate and essential needs of the most vulnerable
communities in the flood-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
At the end of August, more than 2,000 people had been killed
and 5.6 million houses and 1.3 million hectares of crops had been
destroyed by China's worst floods since 1954.
</P>
<P>
Australia had already committed 165,000 Australian dollars for
flood relief efforts through the International Federation of Red
Cross and Red Crescent Societies three months ago, the foreign
minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
