<HEADLINE> Flood-Hit Area Reports Good Grain Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Despite the heavy flooding this
summer, China's northernmost province, Heilongjiang, is expected
to reap 30.1 billion kg of grain this year, the third bumper
harvest in its history.
</P>
<P>
Rainstorms and floods inundated 74 state farms in Heilongjiang,
causing damage to more than 1.36 million hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Provincial agricultural experts attribute the anticipated good
harvest to a number of measures including more acreage for
high-yielding paddy rice and maize, increased government input for
grain production and the application of modern cultivation
techniques.
</P>
<P>
Implementation of these measures has helped increase grain-crop
output by 5.51 billion kg this year, a provincial agricultural
official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
