<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Industry Presents A Gloom Picture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Major industrial sectors in
India saw a sharp fall in demand in the first six months of the
current fiscal year beginning April 1.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Confederation of Indian Industry (CII)
showed that a majority of Indian industries had less than 10
percent or negative growth rate in the first half of the fiscal
year 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
The biggest slump had been experienced by the automobile sector
which saw a 41 percent dip in commercial vehicles production, 53
percent in middle and heavy commercial vehicles, 20 percent in
light commercial vehicle and three percent in cars, according to
the Financial Express daily here Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper said, motor cycles experienced a 27 percent
growth in production during the period.
</P>
<P>
Growth in the basic goods sector also remained depressed with
only 2.5 percent increase in aluminum, 5.4 percent in cement, 5.2
percent in fertilizer but the production of cold rolled steel and
lead and lead alloy decreased 2.5 and 13 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the intermediate goods segment, production in polyester
staple fiber and polyester filament yarn grew 12.6 and 17.4
percent respectively while production in capital goods was low.
</P>
<P>
Tractors production showed a plunge of five percent, machine
tools decreased by 27.4 percent and textile machinery saw a dip of
25 percent, the Financial Express said.
</P>
<P>
Industries performing well in terms of production from April to
September included color television sets (26 percent),
refrigerators (22 percent), air conditioners (30 percent) and
hardware (25 percent).
</P>
<P>
The sales and exports figures mentioned in the CII report
clearly indicated that the Indian economy was faced with a slump
with commercial vehicles facing a 29.1 percent dip in production
and medium and heavy vehicles a 37.1 percent decrease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
