<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Berger: U.S.-Russia Ties Not to Be Affected by Air Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Sunday that possible air strikes by the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) against Serbian targets will not affect its
relationship with Russia.
</P>
<P>
In "Late Edition" show of the Cable News Network (CNN), U.S.
President Bill Clinton's National Security Adviser Sandy Berger
said "certainly we have to act in a way which we believe is in our
interest and in NATO's interest."
</P>
<P>
"I do not believe that will affect our fundamental relationship
with Russia," Berger said.
</P>
<P>
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev warned a week ago that
NATO military strikes to force a settlement in Kosovo would mean a
return to the Cold War while a Russian general Saturday said that
Moscow could consider military cooperation with Yugoslavia if NATO
goes ahead with air strikes.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov played down any suggestion
of a renewed Cold War in an interview aired on Russian Television
on Sunday, but said it it could lead to international chaos.
</P>
<P>
Berger told the CNN that it was up to Yugoslavia's President
Slobodan Milosevic to avert NATO air strikes by complying with
U.N. demands to withdraw Serbian forces from Kosovo, to allow
humanitarian aid into the province and to begin talks with ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"The ball now is in Mr. Milosevic's court. He can come into
compliance or he can face military action by NATO," said Berger.
</P>
<P>
U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke on Sunday continued talks in
Belgrade into the night with Milosevic to try to resolve the
Kosovo crisis after hours of negotiations producing no
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
NATO is expected to issue an activation order on Monday for the
air strikes.
</P>
<P>
Berger said that if military action is ordered, it would not be
"confined only Kosovo," suggesting that targets in whole Serbia
could be attacked.
</P>
<P>
He added that a monitoring mission will be needed if Belgrade
agrees to comply fully with the U.N. Security Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
"If Mr. Milosevic complies over the next few days, next few
hours, it will obviously require some sort of a verification
mission on the ground to determine whether he is living up to
those promises," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that the mission should be civilian, in
which the U.S. will not take part. "There may be some NATO role.
There will be no U.S. combat forces." he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
