<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Govt Urged to Probe Previous Regime's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka government has
been urged to probe activities of the previous United National
Party (UNP) government concerning the funding to the rebels of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), the official Daily News
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga has taken cognizance of an
appeal by government back benchers to initiate such a probe, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The back benchers have alleged that the UNP leadership had
provided millions of rupees, truck loads of arms and ammunition
and cement to the LTTE.
</P>
<P>
They said there are still leaders in the UNP who were also in
office during the administration of the late president Ranasinghe
Premadasa when arms and funds were donated to the LTTE.
</P>
<P>
General Sepala Attygala, former army commander and secretary to
the Ministry of Defense, had revealed that the quality of the
ammunition presented to the LTTE had not even been available to
the Sri Lanka army.
</P>
<P>
They had been supplied on the basis of a collective Cabinet
decision that the arms were meant for the armed forces. There had
been ten truck loads of self loading rifles, T-56 assault rifles
and Browning automatic pistols which were channeled to the LTTE
through the army.
</P>
<P>
The back benchers pointed out that what the UNP leaders had
done was unpatriotic and amounted to treason. Hence a commission
of inquiry to fully probe the allegations was urgently required.
</P>
<P>
The UNP leadership had supplied arms to the LTTE during the
latter's peace talks with the then government of president
Ranasinghe Premadasa to whom they gave assurances of cooperation
to get rid of the Indian Peace Keeping Force (IPKF) who were
present in the north and east of Sri Lanka from August 1987 to
March 1990.
</P>
<P>
The IPKF came to Sri Lanka following a peace agreement signed
in July 1987 by former president J.R. Jayewardene and former
Indian prime minister Rajiv Gandhi to contain the Tamil rebels and
evolve a political solution to the country's ethnic problem.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, president Premadasa won his election on a pledge to
eject the IPKF from the country. To achieve this, he negotiated
with the LTTE and reached some agreements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
