<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Provide Air Corridor to NATO in "Emergency" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Supreme National
Defense Council announced Sunday that Romania will grant access to
its airspace to NATO "in case of emergency."
</P>
<P>
The decision was made in response to a NATO request two days
ago asking Romania to provide air corridor for its possible
strikes against Yugoslavia, said Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu.
</P>
<P>
The council, composed of the president, prime minister, defense
minister, foreign minister and other key figures, met to discuss
the Kosovo situation and Romania's stand on possible NATO armed
intervention.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued by the council said Romania has all along
supported the efforts to settle the crisis through negotiations
while backing all measures to be taken by the international
community on the matter.
</P>
<P>
But as a neighbor of Yugoslavia, Romania will not directly
participate in any military actions there.
</P>
<P>
Romania is ready to send a humanitarian multi-function mobile
team to Yugoslavia to engage in medical relief, refugee
arrangement and housing rebuilding, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
Dorin Marian, National Defense and State Security Advisor, told
the press that NATO's planes were to use Romanian airspace only
"in case of emergency" -- dangerous situation due to technical
breakdowns and inability to return to home bases for unexpected
reasons.
</P>
<P>
Romanian political parties were divided in their reaction to
the communique. Many appreciated the non-participation decision in
NATO military operation in Yugoslavia and considered it to be in
line with international practice to offer Romania's airspace to
NATO in emergency.
</P>
<P>
But others emphasized that Romania should not provide any help
to NATO by noting that to open airspace is equal to providing
logistic assistance to it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
