<HEADLINE> Southeast European Women Conference Focuses on Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- An international conference of
women in the 21st Century opened here Sunday with its focus on the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The meeting "Transcending Boundaries to Sustainable Development
in Southeast Europe" was attended by 335 representatives of
non-governmental organizations in the region.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian President Peter Stoyanov said at the opening ceremony
that the developments in Kosovo were in the focus of the world
attention.
</P>
<P>
U.S. first lady Hillary Clinton, a special guest to the
conference, said "those of us with a voice and power to use must
speak out for the ethnic Albanians who are suffering in Kosovo. We
must speak out for the 250,000 people left without a home."
</P>
<P>
The lack of an effective civil society is at the root of the
problems in Kosovo, said Sonja Liht of the Open Society Foundation
in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"We are witnessing atrocities in Kosovo, as people are being
killed, houses burnt and thousands of people are seeking refuge in
the mountains waiting for the world to intervene," said Mrs Lidra
Mejdani, wife of the Albanian president.
</P>
<P>
Antonina Stoyanova, wife of the Bulgarian president, said she
hopes this conference would help reach an agreement on the
principles of future development and contribute to establishing a
new image of the region.  
</P>
