<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Individual Income Tax Increases in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 12 (Xinhua) -- About 600,000 residents of
Shenzhen, south China, are now paying individual income tax,
contributing greatly to the government coffers.
</P>
<P>
When the special economic zone began to levy individual income
tax ten years ago, the tax was minimal, and only a small number of
people were required to pay it.
</P>
<P>
With the fast growth in people's income, individual income tax
payment nearly doubled between 1995 and 1997, making it the third
largest local tax category, behind only business tax and
enterprise income tax.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, Shenzhen, with a permanent and
transient population of 3.5 million, collected 692 million yuan
(83.37 million U.S. dollars) in individual income tax. This amount
is expected to top 1.2 billion yuan for the entire year, a more
than 20 percent rise over last year.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1.05 billion yuan collected in 1997, individual income
tax paid by foreigners accounted for 260 million yuan, or 25
percent. The local tax authorities promulgated rules to further
standardize collection to facilitate foreign tax payers this year.
</P>
<P>
Since more of the taxes are coming from income earned from
stock investments, the city also circulated a document concerning
this type of collection. Last year, the tax from stock-investment
income reached 130 million yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
