<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cattle-born Diseases Hurt Thailand's Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Diseases brought across the
border by smuggled cattle have caused Thailand a loss of 20,000
million baht (500 million U.S. dollars) annually in revenue from
export of livestock and related products, according to Deputy
Agriculture and Cooperatives Minister Somchai Sunthornwat.
</P>
<P>
Before 1995, over one million head of cattle were smuggled
across the border from Myanmar, Laos and Cambodia through 26 Thai
provinces, bringing with them foot and mouth disease and authrax.
</P>
<P>
The Livestock Development Department has failed to make the
country free of animal diseases due to the smuggling although a
program for this purpose has been launched for over 10 years
during which over 1,000 million baht (25 million U.S. dollars) has
been spent.
</P>
<P>
Many countries wanted to import livestock from Thailand, but
the uncontrollable spread of foot and mouth disease compelled them
to change their minds, causing Thailand to lose about 20,000
million baht (500 million U.S. dollars) annually in revenue,
Somchai was quoted Monday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Japan, in particular, wanted to import Thai pigs on condition
that they are free of disease, he said.
</P>
<P>
As part of the effort to stop the spread of diseases across the
border, Thailand has set up eight border animal checkpoints where
imported cattle are put in quarantine and vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
Somchai said that his ministry intends to impose disease
control on all imported animals and make Thailand free of foot and
mouth disease by 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
