<HEADLINE> Rich Oil-Gas Layers Found in Qaidam Basin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Rich layers of oil and gas have
been found in the oil-rich northern area of the Qaidam Basin,
China's future onshore oil and gas production base in the
northwest.
</P>
<P>
One of the basin's operating oils has been verified as having
31 gas layers of 69.9 meters thick, and another well proved to
have 13 oil layers of 43.4 meters thick.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai Oil Field is the fourth largest natural gas field
in China. The northern part of the Qaidam Basin has been found to
have the brightest exploration prospects in the Qinghai Oil Field,
with oil reserves expected to reach 1.7 billion tons and natural
gas reserves, 300 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Last year, new natural gas reserves totaling 75 billion cubic
meters were found in the Da'erxun Lake area in the northern part
of the basin. Also, a 1,727-meter-thick oil layer was discovered
in the Lenghu Lake area, also in the northern region.
</P>
<P>
The total verified oil and natural gas reserves of the basin
now stand at four billion tons and 150 billion cubic
meters respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Province Hastens Marine Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province has become a marine economic giant of China.
</P>
<P>
It has now established a complete fishing, processing,
transporting and trade system, and its ocean-going operation
extends from the Pacific to the Atlantic and Indian oceans.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province gained 35 billion yuan from the sea,
accounting for 17 percent of the country's total marine output
value.
</P>
<P>
It built ships with a tonnage of more than one million last
year, an all-time high and half of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Development of offshore tourism in six coastal cities attracted
388,000 visitors from abroad in 1997, netting 259 million
U.S. dollars, up 15 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
At present, Liaoning's offshore oilfields turn out 300,000 tons
of crude oil annually valued at 270 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The province has 175 berths, which handled 100 million tons of
cargo and 5.5 million passengers last year.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Provincial Marine Bureau predicts that the
annual marine output value of Liaoning will reach 63 billion yuan
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The province has 266 islands and its coastal line is 2,920 km
long.  
</P>
</TEXT>
