<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 11 (Xinhua) -- A former leader of the Communist
Refoundation Party of Italy announced Sunday that he will form a
"new Communist Party" after last week's split that brought down
the center-left coalition government of Prime Minister Romano
Prodi.
</P>
<P>
Armando Cossutta, former party president last week broke away
from the Communist Refoundation Party led by Fausto Bertinotti
because of its decision to withdraw support for the government in
a parliamentary confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
Cossutta and his supporters going for Prodi in the vote, but
were one vote short of the number needed to save the government.
</P>
<P>
Cossutta told some 3,000 supporters gathered in a Rome cinema
that the new party would be ready to participate in next month's
regional elections in Rome.
</P>
<P>
Cossutta is expected to lead the party with Oliviero Diliberto
as party secretary.
</P>
<P>
At the gathering, he also launched a strong attack on
Bertinotti, saying he had "the grave responsibility for the
(government) crisis which opened the door to the worst forces of
the right." 
</P>
