<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USOC Shelves Expanded Drug Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Olympic Committee
decided to shelf a plan to test for recreational drug use among
athletes.
</P>
<P>
Also striped from a revision of the committee's drug-test
rules was a proposal to tighten security around urine samples.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the USOC started unannounced, random drug
tests of residents at training centers in several American
cities.
</P>
<P>
The addition of recreational drugs such as marijuana and
cocaine to thetests would have formalized anti-doping efforts the
USOC takes only when specifically asked by member sports bodies.
</P>
<P>
The USOC is due to hear next April from a task force
investigating how to place all drug testing of American's
Olympic-level athletes to an independent agency.
</P>
<P>
The USOC is one of the few national Olympic groups that
conducts its own drug tests. The USOC wants to set up an
indenpendent drug-testing agency to guarantee fairness and
promote trust. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
