<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Gross Foreign Exchange Reserves Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's central bank, Bank
Indonesia, announced that its gross foreign exchange reserves rose
to 21.5 billion U.S. dollars in the week ending October 7 from
20.5 billion U.S. dollars the previous week.
</P>
<P>
In its latest weekly report, the central bank said that the
increase was due to the disbursement of the International Monetary
Fund's fresh monthly loan of 936.7 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But its net international reserves (NIR) fell slightly to 13.94
billion U.S. dollars as of October 7 from 14.03 billion U.S.
dollars a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
The decline was mainly due to servicing the interest of the
government's foreign debt and selling U.S. dollars for rupiah to
sterilize liquidity in the wake of greater government spending,
the Jakarta Post Monday quoted the central bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the October 7 NIR level was still above the
International Monetary Fund's adjusted NIR target of 11.67 billion
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
