<HEADLINE> Hungary Asked to Open Airspace to NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) has officially requested Hungary to offer free
passage to its planes over the Hungarian airspace for a possible
air strike against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian Prime Minister Orban Viktor disclosed this on
television broadcast Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
Orban said he would ask the National Assembly to convene an
urgent session for approving NATO's request.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile he emphasized the precondition for Hungary's
cooperation with NATO, saying "we need appropriate security
guarantee, that is NATO should extend its defence cooperation
system to our country."
</P>
<P>
Orban noted he had made his stand clear both in his recent
visit to the United States and his telephone talks with Brussels,
where NATO Headquarters is based.
</P>
<P>
But he believed that Hungary will get NATO protection once it
suffers military revenge from Yugoslavia due to its cooperation
with the NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
