<HEADLINE> Bulgaria To Grant NATO Free Passage in East-West Direction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria will grant the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) free passage through the
country's airspace in its possible air strikes against Yugoslavia,
Deputy Foreign Minister Marin Raikov said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
If necessary, Bulgaria will grant NATO free air passage in the
East-West direction only, Raikov said, adding that the passage
will only be for aircraft that have already been to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Bulgaria will ask NATO for guarantees of its
national security on the basis of the Partnership for Peace
Framework Agreement and the Agreement between NATO members and the
states participating in Partnership for Peace, Raikov said.
</P>
<P>
According to Government Information Service, Prime Minister
Ivan Kostov Saturday received an official note from NATO
requesting for passage through Bulgarian airspace.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian government said that it believed there are still
chances for a peaceful settlement of the conflict in the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Kostov said that Bulgaria will help only humanitarian
and logistic operations within the framework of NATO efforts to
impose and guarantee peace in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He vowed that his country will not take part, directly or
indirectly, in any military actions in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981012.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Keep Tight Monetary Policy: Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia will stick to
its tight monetary policy until worries over the rupiah exchange
rate and inflation truly subside, the Jakarta Post Monday quoted
bank director Achjar Iljas as saying.
</P>
<P>
Achjar said pressure on the rupiah would remain high until
local corporations with huge overseas debts managed to reschedule
their obligations, while primary pressure on inflation might come
from the expectation of higher inflation.
</P>
<P>
"The momentum is good, but we don't want to be too premature in
lowering interest rates. But if the current stable condition
continues, it will be enough for us to gradually lower the rates.
Our tight monetary policy is only temporary," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah strengthened significantly against the U.S. dollar
last week, ending at 9,050 rupiah Friday, compared with more than
10,000 rupiah last month and 15,000 rupiah in June.
</P>
<P>
Achjar attributed the rupiah appreciation to improving
sentiment in regional currencies following the strengthening of
the Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
"But is this sustainable? We're still observing. This is a good
opportunity, but we have to be careful because if we relax the
tight monetary condition it could create potential demand for
dollars," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the more than 20 billion U.S. dollars in
the country's private sector overseas debt due this year presented
a huge potential demand for U.S. dollars, with accompanying
pressure on the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
If the interest rates were cut immediately amid the existing
huge potential demand for the U.S. dollars, the debtors would rush
to borrow the rupiah to purchase the U.S. dollar, he said.
</P>
<P>
Achjar added that another important factor to watch was the
inflation rate which had started to decrease but "is it
sustainable?"
</P>
<P>
The Central Bureau of Statistics announced last week that the
inflation rate for September was 3.75 percent compared with 6.30
percent in August.
</P>
<P>
"How can this trend be maintained? It all depends on food
supply, distribution and political stability," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
