<HEADLINE> U.S. Olympic Panel Increases Athlete Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Olympic Committee
has decided to put up 18 million U.S. dollars to boost American
athletes to win more medals at the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
The money was budgeted Saturday as the board met in Phoenix
and approved its budget through 2002.
</P>
<P>
The funds will be directed to the USOC's Podium 2002 program,
designed to foster athlete development, said USOC Executive
Director Dick Schultz.
</P>
<P>
"We're really excited about this," Schultz said. "This is a
new way of doing things for the U.S. Olympic Committee."
</P>
<P>
The United States won 13 medals at the 1994 Winter Games at
Lillehammer, and equaled that total at Nagano, Japan, last winter.
</P>
<P>
Schultz said:"Our program is going in the wrong direction." To
keep and increase public support, the United States must win more
medals, he added.
</P>
<P>
Before the directors approved the budget, the Podium 2002
program had already planned to spend 3.4 million U.S. dollars,
most of it on direct athlete support, Schultz said.
</P>
<P>
Theremaining 14.6 million will go to the Salt Lake Organizing
Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
