<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Terror for Indonesian Activist Working With Rape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The terror for the Indonesian
activist working with rape victims of May riots continued Sunday
with the news that the house of a fellow activist was broken into
by a group of men, the Indonesian Observer reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hajjah Sundus A. Salim, fellow activist of the Team of
Volunteers for Humanity, was quoted as saying that the men stole
her son's motorcycle after she received two threats over the
phone.
</P>
<P>
The new terror follows the death of Martadinata, also known as
Ita, the 18-year-old daughter of an activist with the Team of
Volunteers for Humanity.
</P>
<P>
The victim was found with her neck slashed and stab wounds on
her hands, abdomen and chest Friday by her parents at their home
in Central Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Police investigators Sunday insisted the incident had been a
purely criminal act.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Jakarta Police Chief Maj. Gen. Noegroho
Djajoesman said police had arrested Suryadi, a 20-year-old
neighbor of the victim.
</P>
<P>
"He (Suryadi) committed the crime because he wanted to steal
some money to help his parents," said Noegroho, adding that the
motive of the violent crime was criminal, and not politically
motivated.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chairman of the Indonesian Legal Aid and Human Rights
Association Paskah Irianto said Sunday that he believed Ita was
one of the rape victims of the May riots.
</P>
<P>
He said Ita was about to recount her assault in the United
States in the next few days. "I think that for her safety, Ita was
named a volunteer who would accompany the rape victims to testify
in the U.S.," he added.
</P>
<P>
Volunteers team coordinator Sandyawan Sumardi told the Jakarta
Post that he did not know for sure if Ita was a rape victim.
</P>
<P>
"But, to be frank, I also suspected that Ita was a rape victim.
How could a girl her age accompany rape victims? What is her role
in the planned journey to the U.S. if she was not a victim?" he
asked.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Ita's death, several activists complained of
continuous terrorization, including threats of possible physical
and sexual assaults.
</P>
<P>
Both Ita and her mother had been involved in providing
counseling and assistance for many ethnic-Chinese Indonesian women
raped during last May's riots in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Humanitarian workers had speculated that the brutal murder of
the activist was an attempt to cow them into silence.
</P>
<P>
"The killing was done to warn the activists not to go further
with their investigation," said Ester Indahyani Jusuf Lubis,
chairwoman of Solidaritas Nusa Bangsa, which was formed in June to
fight racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
Although she admitted the murder was a terrible blow to the
activists, Ester vowed to continue with her work to uncover facts
behind the May riots, which left about 1,200 people dead.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before a gathering of more than 5,000 people in
Central Jakarta Sunday, Abdurrahman Wahid, general chairman of the
Nahdlatul Ulama (NU), the country's largest Muslim organization,
deplored the murder of Ita, saying it was "unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
"Why does one have to be murdered just because one wanted to
testify? We reject such inhumane means. We are a civilized
nation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Team of Volunteers for Humanity was the first organization
to raise the alarm about the systematic gang-rapes during the May
riots. Led by Catholic priest Sandyawan Sumardi, the
non-governmental organization reported to the National Commission
on Human Rights in July that at least 168 women and children were
raped or sexually abused during the riots in Jakarta and other
cities.
</P>
<P>
The government established a team in July which includes
representatives from the Armed Forces (ABRI), government agencies,
the rights body and non-governmental organizations to investigate
allegations that the riots were masterminded. The team is expected
to complete its task later this month.
</P>
<P>
National Police Chief Lt. Gen. Roesmanhadi said in August that
some non-governmental organizations were exaggerating reports of
rapes and sexual assaults against Chinese-Indonesian women during
the riots.
</P>
<P>
Armed Forces (ABRI) Commander Gen. Wiranto has also repeatedly
said that ABRI had found no evidence to substantiate the claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
