<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Alstom Provides Subway Trains for Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Alstom, a major French
transportation equipment supplier, is helping to build the subway
system in Shanghai, China's largest industrial center.
</P>
<P>
The latest effort came when a letter of intent was signed
recently between Alstom and a local subway construction company,
on the supply of equipment valued at 200 million U.S. dollars for
the third subway line of a viaduct in the city.
</P>
<P>
According to the pact, Alstom will provide 24 subway trains,
each with six cars, which are said to cost less in electricity and
maintenance and will be put into operation by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The subway project is expected to ease the increasing traffic
pressure in the largest metropolitan area in China.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Bilger, Alstom's president, said that his company's
development in China has been further promoted by the Shanghai
project. He hoped that Alstom would undertake more subway projects
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Alstom has already provided nearly a third of China's imported
locomotives, and now has 3,500 employees working in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
