<HEADLINE> Greece's First Round of Local Government Elections Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Greece's first round of local
government elections ended Sunday night with main
opposition-backed candidates having the lead in the country's
three largest municipalities.
</P>
<P>
In the Greek capital of Athens, incumbent mayor Dimitris
Avramopoulos, supported by main opposition New Democracy (ND)
party, was re-elected in Sunday's first round of the local
elections. In the northern Greek city of Thessaloniki, ND backed
candidate Vasilis Papageorgopoulos has so far amassed 42.6 percent
of the votes while in the port city of Piraeus, some 15 kilometers
west of Athens, the main opposition's candidate Ch. Agrapides has
won 42.6 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
Both in Thessaloniki and Piraeus, as well as in other major
cities, there were no outright winners, with the top two
candidates having to brace for the second round of elections which
will take place on October 18.
</P>
<P>
About 8.9 million voters have registered for the elections, the
first since the extensive re-drawing of the local government map
and merger of small communities into larger municipal units.
</P>
<P>
Voters will elect 898 mayors, 54 prefects and 133 heads of
communities in the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
